{"title_page": "William Ingle", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = William Ingle\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = St James Boroughbridge (105).JPG\n| image_size       = 250px\n| alt              = William Ingle aged about 24 years, by Robert Mawer\n| caption          = Portrait of William Ingle aged about 24 years, by Robert Mawer, in St James' Church, [[Boroughbridge]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. --> 1828\n| birth_place      = [[Bishop Thornton]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|1870|03|25|1828|MM|DD}} --> 25 March 1870, aged 41 years\n| death_place      = [[Leeds]]\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = British\n| residence        = 38 Portland Crescent, Leeds\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = Architectural sculpture on:<br />[[Mill Hill Chapel]], 1848<br />Moorlands House, Leeds, 1854<br />[[Leeds Town Hall]], 1854<br />30 Park Place, Leeds, 1865<br />[[Endcliffe Hall]], [[Sheffield]], 1865<br />Commercial Bank, [[Bradford]], 1868\n| style            = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]<br />[[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]]\n| movement         = [[Aesthetic movement]]<br />[[Romanticism]]<br />[[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]<br>[[Neoclassicism]]\n| spouse           = Ann Elizabeth Agar\n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n}}\n\n'''William Ingle''' (1828 - 25 March 1870) was an architectural sculptor in [[Leeds, West Yorkshire]], England. He specialised in delicately undercut bas relief and small stand-alone stone sculptures of natural and imaginary flora and fauna on churches and on civic, commercial and domestic buildings. He was apprenticed to his uncle [[Robert Mawer]]. After Mawer's death in 1854 he worked in partnership with his aunt [[Catherine Mawer]] and his cousin [[Charles Mawer]] in the company [[Mawer and Ingle]]. Notable works by Ingle exist on [[Leeds Town Hall]], [[Endcliffe Hall]], [[Sheffield]] and Moorlands House, Leeds. He sometimes exhibited gentle humour in his ecclesiastical work, such as faces peering through greenery, and mischievous humour on secular buildings, such as comic rabbits and frogs among foliage. He died of [[tuberculosis]] at age 41 years, having suffered the disease for two years.\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:William Ingle parents (1).jpg|thumb|right|Gravestone of Ingle's parents]]\nWilliam Ingle (1828 - 25 March 1870)<ref name=\"W.Ingle death cert\" >{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=IQsMp7Felj7V%2B2HV%2BWDvWA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=23 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Mar 1870 Ingle William 41 Leeds vol9b p359. The certificate says: 26 March 1870, 73 Portland Crescent, William Ingle, male, 41 years, Phthisis 2 years, certified, Ann Agar of 27 St James St Leeds present at the death.</ref> was the nephew of Robert and Catherine Mawer, and cousin of their son Charles Mawer.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 31 Mar 1855\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The nobility, clergy and gentry |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000336/18550331/052/0001 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Times |location= |date=31 March 1855 |page=1 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> He was the eldest son of Robert Ingle (1799 \u2013 2 August 1860), a corn miller at [[List of mills in North Yorkshire#Bishop Thornton|Render Mills, Bishop Thornton]], and Elizabeth Ingle nee Mawer (1802 \u2013 18 November 1845), sister of the sculptor Robert Mawer.<ref>United Kingdom Census 1841: HO/107/1351/5/10 p.14, Bishop Thornton, Render Mills</ref> Robert Ingle and Elizabeth Mawer were married at Ripon Cathedral on 3 October 1825. They were both buried at Bishop Thornton. William Ingle was baptised on 30 June 1828 at [[Bishop Thornton]], [[North Yorkshire]].<ref>England, Births and Christenings, 1538-1975. Salt Lake City, Utah: FamilySearch, 2013</ref>\n\n===Apprenticeship===\nAssuming the regular pattern of apprenticeship between the ages of 14 and 21 years, Ingle was apprenticed to Robert Mawer between about 1842 and 1849.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 31 Mar 1855\" />\n\n===Family life and career===\n[[File:Old Commercial Bank Bradford 065a.jpg|thumb|right|Portrait of William Ingle aged about 39 years, after contracting [[Tuberculosis|TB]], carved by Catherine Mawer. The feather in his cap celebrates his successful work on the Commercial Bank, [[Bradford]]]]\nHe married Ann Elizabeth Agar (b. 1832 at Kimpton, Yorkshire), daughter of Benjamin Agar, an estate agent, in 1852 at Leeds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=ROSFVCHUYgJNs3TSvwY14Q&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=23 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Marriages Jun 1852, Agar Ann Elizabeth and Ingle William, Leeds vol9b p287</ref> In 1851, at age 22, he was living at a lodging house in Leeds, describing himself as a stone and wood carver.<ref>United Kingdom Census 1851: H.O.107/2321/25 Leeds, 4 Bentick Street</ref> By 1861 he and his wife were living at 38 Portland Crescent, Leeds, and William described himself as a sculptor and stone carver in the Census that year. They had four children: Amelia Jane (b.1852),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=GFPX%2F0rJUYitZaq5Nlsrbg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1852 Ingle Amelia Jane Leeds vol9b p359, (She married in 1874 and/or 1881)</ref> Arthur Robert (1855-1865),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=rt67OXC8IsUi8itUwIwMVQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Mar 1865 Ingle Arthur Robert Leeds vol9b p350</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=dDmDUPyFaGbqU4aDwBR5RQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1855 Ingle Arthur Robert Leeds vol9b p350</ref> Fred (1861-1875),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=6pajAr8cirfs4YBgKC3ECw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1861 Ingle Fred Leeds vol9b p370</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=PKa4GR5ZTPpxTFp5Am6PQg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Jun 1875 Ingle Fred 13 Leeds vol9b p328</ref> and Ernest (1866-1955),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=MySY1WkiD4Rqx%2FUeeYj2Hg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1866 Ingle Ernest Leeds vol9b p444</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=VG4sbQGfBzgibpQHKOGvhw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Mar 1955 Ingle Ernest 88 Wharfedale vol2d p789</ref> all born in Leeds. Ernest was described in the 1871 Census as \"deaf and dumb from birth.\"<ref>United Kingdom Census 1861: RG9/3394 p16 Leeds Portland Crescent.</ref><ref name=\"1871 Census Agar\" >United Kingdom Census 1871: RG10/4566/ West Leeds, 55 St James Street</ref>\n\nIngle was a member of the Mawer Group, a closely-associated group of architectural sculptors working in Leeds in the 19th century. The group included Robert Mawer, Catherine Mawer, Charles Mawer, Benjamin Payler, Matthew Taylor, and Ingle himself. Unlike the other sculptors in this group, Ingle was never credited by personal name for his work, by contemporary newspapers and other documents; they always referred to the company Mawer and Ingle. He was employed as a sculptor by master sculptor Robert Mawer from about 1849 until Robert Mawer's death in 1854, when Ingle became a master sculptor himself. So long as Ingle was working from the Mawer stoneyard, it produced various carving styles including finely undercut natural vegetation, and natural and comical wildlife and mythical animals. After he died, such natural, realistic elements were no longer produced in the same delicate style, so it is reasonable to suppose that this was Ingle's work. Ingle superintended the stone yard and onsite works under the management of Catherine Mawer after Robert Mawer's death,<ref name=\"Leeds Times 31 Mar 1855\" /> then became a partner in the firm of Mawer & Ingle.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Deaths |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000686/18700402/169/0012 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencee |location= |date=2 April 1870 |page=12 |access-date=13 March 2019}} \"Ingle, March 25 1870, aged 41, Mr William Ingle, of the firm of Messrs Mawer & Ingle, stone carvers, Great George Street, Leeds.\"</ref>\n\n[[Leeds Civic Trust]] arranged to unveil two [[blue plaque]]s At the [[Henry Moore Foundation|Henry Moore Institute]] on 11 July 2019, commemorating the work of Robert Mawer, Catherine Mawer and William Ingle, besides the Mawer Group as a whole. This plaques were to be affixed to Moorlands House, Albion Street, and 30 Park Place, both in Leeds, at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinson |first=Andrew HUTC |title=Blue plaques to honour Leeds architectural sculptors who left their mark on some of city's most iconic buildings |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/people/blue-plaques-to-honour-leeds-architectural-sculptors-who-left-their-mark-on-some-of-city-s-most-iconic-buildings-1-9863859 |via= |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location= |date=8 July 2019 |page= |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nWilliam Ingle died aged 41 years on 26 March 1870, at 73 Portland Crescent, Leeds.  He had had [[tuberculosis]] for two years. His mother in law Ann Agar was present at his death.<ref name=\"W.Ingle death cert\" />\n\n==Blue plaque in Leeds==\n[[File:Mawer Group of sculptors blue plaque (4).jpg|thumb|right|Blue plaque for William Ingle]]\nAt the [[Henry Moore Foundation|Henry Moore Institute]] on 11 July 2019, [[Leeds Civic Trust]] unveiled two [[blue plaque]]s in recognition of the Mawer Group. One of them commemorates the work of William Ingle on 30 Park Place, Leeds. It was scheduled to be affixed to the building at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinson |first=Andrew HUTC |title=Blue plaques to honour Leeds architectural sculptors who left their mark on some of city's most iconic buildings|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/people/blue-plaques-to-honour-leeds-architectural-sculptors-who-left-their-mark-on-some-of-city-s-most-iconic-buildings-1-9863859 |via= |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds, West Yorkshire, England |date=8 July 2019 |page= |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Drysdal |first=Laura |title=A trailblazer for Barbara Hepworth - this is why 'forgotten' sculptor Catherine Mawer has been recognised with a blue plaque in Leeds |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/retro/a-trailblazer-for-barbara-hepworth-this-is-why-forgotten-sculptor-catherine-mawer-has-been-recognised-with-a-blue-plaque-in-leeds-1-9872620 |via= |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds, West Yorkshire, England |date=12 July 2019 |page= |access-date=12 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Works for Robert Mawer==\n{{main|Robert Mawer}}\n\n[[File:Moorlands House Leeds (4).JPG|thumb|right|Sheep's head symbolising the Fleece, or Leeds' source of income (1855) by William Ingle, on Moorlands House]]\n* Church of St Paul and St Jude, [[Manningham, Bradford|Manningham]], 1846\u22121848.<ref name=\"BO 28 Sep 1848 Memorial of SP\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Memorial of St Paul' Church, Manningham |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18480928/021/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=28 September 1848 |page=6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Animal drain-pipe gargoyles.\n* [[Mill Hill Chapel|Mill Hill Unitarian Chapel]], Leeds, 1847-1848.<ref name=\"Preston Chronicle 30 Dec 1848\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New Unitarian Chapel at Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000099/18481230/013/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Preston Chronicle |location= |date=30 December 1848 |page=3 |access-date=13 March 2019}} \"Mawer\" mis-spelled as \"Macor\"</ref> Animal cornice reliefs, fauna and vegetation on reredos, drain-pipe gargoyles, animal and vegetation on pulpit.\n* Church of St Matthew, Bankfoot, [[City of Bradford|Bradford]], 1848\u20131849.<ref name=\"bradford Observer 11dec1849\" >{{cite news|last=From |first=a correspondent  |title=The Church of St Matthew Bankfoot in the parish of Bradford Yorkshire |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18491213/024/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=13 December 1849 |page=6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Vegetation on capitals, drain-pipe gargoyles\n* [[St Michael and All Angels Church, Shelf, West Yorkshire|St Michael and All Angels, Shelf]], Halifax, 1849\u20131850.<ref name=\"Morning Post 24jun1850\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the Church of st Michael and All Angels |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18500624/004/0002 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Morning Post |location= |date=24 June 1850 |page=2 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (No work by Ingle yet identified)\n* St Mary the Virgin, [[Quarry Hill, Leeds]], restoration 1850.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the Church of St. Mary the Virgin, Gomersal |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18510405/040/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=5 April 1851 |page=8, col.3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Church of St Mary the Virgin, [[Gomersal]], 1850-1851.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 1feb1851\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Church of St Mary the Virgin, Little Gomersal, near Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18510201/056/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=1 February 1851 |page=8 col4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving is as yet unexamined)\n* St Catherine, [[Barmby Moor]], restoration 1851\u22121852.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 17 Apr 1852\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The re-opening of St Catherine's Church, Barmby Moor |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18520417/037/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=17 April 1852 |page=7 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving is as yet unexamined)\n* Church of St James, [[Boroughbridge]], 1851\u22121852.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 31 Jul 1852\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the new church at Boroughbridge |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18520731/023/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archives |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=31 July 1852 |page=6 col.1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (No carving by Ingle yet found)\n* [[St George's Hall, Bradford]], 1849-1853.<ref name=\"Bradford Observer 1 Sep 1853 opening\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Opening of st George's Hall. Description of the hall |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18530901/027/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=1 September 1853 |page=6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Vine leaves with grapes, Corinthian capitals.\n* Former St Andrew, Listerhills Road, [[City of Bradford|North Horton]], 1853.<ref name=\"Bradford Observer 29 Sep 1853\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of t Andrew's Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18530929/021/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=29 September 1853 |page=5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* St Mark, [[Woodhouse, Leeds]], 1853 and 1856.<ref name=\"LI 5 Nov 1853 font\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=St Marks Church, Woodhouse |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18531105/014/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=5 November 1853 |page=5 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Some tower gargoyles may be Ingle's work\n* Old Church of St John the Evangelist, [[New Wortley]], Leeds, 1853.<ref name=\"LI 19 Nov 1853 consecration\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of St John's Church, New Wortley |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18531119/038/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive|newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=19 November 1853 |page=8 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"LI 25 Nov 1865 reredos\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New Wortley Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18651125/018/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=25 November 1865 |page=5, col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* [[St Matthias' Church, Burley|Church of St Matthias, Burley]], Leeds, 1853\u22121854.<ref name=\"LI 11 Nov 1854 consecration\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of Burley Church, near Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18541111/039/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=11 November 1854 |page=8 col.5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving has not yet been examined)\n* Moorlands House, 48 Albion Street, [[Leeds, West Yorkshire|Leeds]], 1852-1855.<ref name=\"LI 17 March 1855 Moorlands\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Leeds and Yorkshire Assurance Company |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18550317/019/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=17 March 1855 |page=5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Bulls' and sheep's heads, acanthus leaf panels.\n* St Cuthbert, [[Ackworth, West Yorkshire|Ackworth]], 1855.<ref name=\"LI 1 Sep 1855\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Second day's proceedings |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18550901/027/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=1 September 1855 |page=7 col3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Possibly some foliage decoration, and a dog in foliage on a capital.\n* Reredos at [[Bradford Cathedral|Bradford Parish Church]], 1854\u22121855.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Parish Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18550823/036/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=23 August 1855 |page=5 col.6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Foliage on former reredos (since demolished)\n\n{{Commons category inline|Robert Mawer}}\n\n==Works for Catherine Mawer==\n{{main|Catherine Mawer}}\n\n[[File:St Peter Barton upon Humber 2017 (68).JPG|thumb|right|Capital (1859), in faux [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] style, featuring green man-animal among natural foliage, in St Peter, Barton upon Humber]]\n* Susannah Blesard monument, St Mark, [[Woodhouse, Leeds|Woodhouse]], 1856.<ref name=\"LI 18 Oct 1856 tomb\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The late Mrs Blesard |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18561018/066/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive|newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=18 October 1856 |page=5 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Flora and fauna on memorial. \n* Former St Mark's, Low Moor, [[City of Bradford|Bradford]], 1855\u22121857.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 14mar1857\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of St Mark's Church, Low Moor, near Bradford |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18570314/051/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive|newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=14 March 1857 |page=6 col6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Foliage on capitals, tympanum of south porch, drainpipe gargoyle, foliage on interior capitals, pulpit and font (interior no longer accessible to public)\n* New Hall for [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]] Mechanics Institution, 1855\u22121857.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 17jan1857\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Halifax Mechanics Institution, inauguration of the new building |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18570117/035/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=17 January 1857 |page=6 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Most of the foliage is by Ingle, while Catherine carved the heads.\n* Church of the Holy Innocents, [[Thornhill Lees]] 1858.<ref name=\"LI 26 Jun 1858 consecration\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the Church of the Holy Innocents, Thornhill |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18580626/030/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=26 June 1858 |page=2 col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Gargoyles on exterior (interior carving has not yet been examined).\n* [[Leeds Town Hall|Town Hall, Leeds]], 1853-1858.<ref name=\"LI 4 Sep 1858\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Queen's visit to Leeds, and the inauguration of the Town Hall |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18580904/095/0013 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=4 September 1858 |page=13 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Foliage and ram's heads on front door panels, arch over front door tympanum, roof pinnacles, sheep on clock tower, Corinthian capitals.\n* Memorial tablet, John the Baptist [[Knaresborough]], 1859\u20131860.<ref name=\"Leeds Mercury 22 March 1860\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Knaresborough: the Powell Memorial Fund |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000076/18600322/015/0004 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Mercury |location= |date=22 March 1860 |page=4 col2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 24 March 1860\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Powell Memorial Fund |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18600324/033/0009 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=24 March 1860 |page=9 col4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> All carving of foliage is by Ingle.\n* [[St Peter's Church, Barton-upon-Humber|St Peter, Barton-upon-Humber]], restoration 1859.<ref name=\"Hull Packet 3 June 1859\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Barton, re-opening of st Peter's Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000065/18590603/026/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Hull Packet |location= |date=3 June 1859 |page=7 col.3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Foliage and fauna on capitals and font, animal heads on colonnade in nave.\n* St Stephen's Church, Bowling Old Lane, [[City of Bradford|Bradford]] 1859\u20131860.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 28 April 1860\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=St Stephen's Church, Bowloing Old Lane |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18600428/037/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=28 April 1860 |page=7 col2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Gargoyles.\n\n{{Commons category inline|Catherine Mawer}}\n\n==Works for Mawer and Ingle==\n{{main|Mawer and Ingle}}\n\n* Former [[Barnsley]] Cemetery chapels, lodges and gateway, 1860\u20131861.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Laying the foundation stones at the new cemetery |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001638/18600602/055/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Barnsley Chronicle, etc. |location= |date=2 June 1860 |page=3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> On remaining entrance archway and colonnade: foliage on capitals and label stops. Includes the only insect carved by the Mawer group. Both chapels demolished.\n* Warehouses, [[Bradford]], 1862.<ref name=\"Bradford Observer 27 Mar 1862\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New warehouses |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18620327/042/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=27 March 1862 |page=5 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Church of St Mary, [[Aldborough, North Yorkshire|Lower Dunsforth]], Boroughbridge, 1861.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 28 Sep 1861\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of St Mary's Church, Low Dunsforth |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18610928/076/0010 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=28 September 1861 |page=10 col.1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving has yet to be examined)\n* Former St Bartholomew's, [[Armley]], Leeds, 1861.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 28 Dec 1861\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Armley Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000336/18611228/025/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Times |location= |date=28 December 1861 |page=5 col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Church of St Ricarius, [[Aberford]], 1862.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 10may1862\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Re-opening and consecration of Aberford Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18620510/064/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=10 May 1862 |page=5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Interior corbels, font.\n* Former St Matthews, [[Chapel Allerton]], 1861-1863.<ref name=\"LI 15 Nov 1862\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Re-opening of St Matthews Church, Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18621115/041/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=15 November 1862 |page=8 col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Reredos at [[Christ Church, High Harrogate]], 1861\u20131862.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 5 Jul 1862\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Enlargement of Christ Church, Harrogate |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18620705/034/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=5 July 1862 |page=5 col.3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Removed and destroyed. Ingle may have carved the \"flowery capitals\" on it.\n* Albert Memorial, [[Queensbury, West Yorkshire|Queensbury]], 1863.<ref name=\"LI 30 May 1863\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Albert Memorial at Queensbury |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18630530/048/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=30 May 1863 |page=6 col.6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Stone panels with foliage and hidden birds, diapering, crocketing.\n* Church of St Peter, [[Bramley, Leeds|Bramley]], 1861-1863.<ref name=\"LI 11 Jul 1863\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of Bramley, new church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18630711/047/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=11 July 1863 |page=8 col.1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Nave demolished and replaced in 20th century, tower remains. Ingle possibly carved gargoyles, pinnacles and capitals on tower. \n* Hepper & Sons auctioneers sales rooms and offices, East Parade, [[Leeds]] 1863.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 5 Dec 1853\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Improvements in street architecture |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000336/18631205/009/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Times |location= |date=5 December 1863 |page=3 col.3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Natural foliage on some capitals.\n* Warehouses, 30 Park Place, Leeds, 1865.<ref name=\"Builder 1865\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Warehouse, Park Place, Leeds |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?q1=Mawer%20Ingle;id=uiug.30112117956455;view=image;start=1;sz=10;page=root;size=100;seq=43;num=33 |via=Hathi Trust |newspaper=The Building News and Engineering Journal, vol.12 |location= |date=1865 |page=33 col.1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> All carving on this building: natural foliage and hidden animals, birds and frogs.\n* [[Endcliffe Hall]], [[Sheffield]], 1863\u20131865.<ref name=\"Sheff Ind 26 May 1865\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The new hall at Endcliffe |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000181/18650527/005/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Sheffield Independent |location= |date=27 May 1865 |page=6 col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>  Naturalistic carving of foliage and animals, including hidden detail throughout.\n*  Former St John the Evangelist, [[Wortley, Leeds]], 1864\u20131865.<ref name=\"LI 25 Nov 1865\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New Wortley Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18651125/018/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=25 November 1865 |page=5 col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Former Holy Trinity, [[Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth]], 1866.<ref name=\"Stam Merc 13 Apr 1866\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Louth - consecration of the Holy Trinity Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000237/18660413/016/0006 |via=british Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Stamford Mercury |location= |date=13 April 1866 |page=6 cl.5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Natural foliage on label stops and capitals.\n* Memorial tablet at Holy Trinity, [[Low Moor, Bradford]], 1866.<ref name=\"Leeds Mercury 7 July 1866\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The late Rev. J. Fawcett |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000076/18660707/012/0005 |via=british Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Mercury |location= |date=7 July 1866 |page=5 col.6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> One of Ingle's foremost works: he executed all carving except the roundel portrait and the dedication panel. Humour is shown in an over-large albatross nest on a delicate pinnacle, the bird imitating a pelican vulning. There are quirky hidden sirens, supposed to bring luck if seen, but requiring a ladder to view.\n* [[Wool Exchange, Bradford]], 1864-1867.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 8 May 1867\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Another statue for Peel Park |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/BL/0000336/18670508/007/0005?browse=true |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Times |location= |date=8 May 1867 |page=5 col.6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Naturalistic foliage on interior capitals.\n* Statues of Sweep and Shoeblack, originally in [[Peel Park, Bradford]], 1867.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 8 May 1867\" /> (Statues now lost)\n* Former Church of St Peter, Dewsbury Road, [[Hunslet|Hunslet Moor]], 1866-1868.<ref name=\"Leeds Mercury 3jul1868\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New churches in Leeds. Consecration of Hunslet Moor Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000076/18680703/012/0004 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Mercury |location= |date=3 July 1868 |page=4 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Commercial Bank, [[Bradford]], 1867-1868.<ref name=\"YP and LI 5 Mar 1868\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New commercial bank, Bradford |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000686/18680305/100/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=5 March 1868 |page=3 col5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Ingle's last major work, the same building featuring a portrait of him with feather in cap by Catherine Mawer. He carved label stops and small stand-alone sculptures featuring natural and fanciful marine animals, including ships' rats and cats.\n* Former Church of St Clement, Chapeltown Road, Leeds, 1867\u20131868.<ref name=\"Leeds Mercury 11sep1868\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Leeds Church Extension Society: consecration of St Clement's Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000076/18680911/010/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Mercury |location= |date=11 September 1868 |page=3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* St John the Evangelist, [[Lepton, West Yorkshire|Lepton]] 1866\u20131868.<ref name=\"Hudd Chronicle 5 Dec 1868\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of a new church at Lepton |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000167/18681205/034/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Huddersfield Chronicle |location= |date=5 December 1868 |page=8 col.3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving is as yet unexamined)\n* Former Unitarian Chapel, Chapel Lane, Bradford, 1869.<ref name=\"YP and LI 4 June 1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Opening of a new Unitarian chapel |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000686/18690604/102/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=4 June 1869 |page=3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Scottish Widows insurance building, Park Row, Leeds, 1869.<ref name=\"YP and LI 26 une 1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Erection of a new insurance building in Park Row |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000686/18690626/150/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=26 June 1869 |page=5 col.6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Only one portico remains; Ingle's original contribution is unknown.\n* United Free Methodists day and infant schools, [[Farsley]], 1869.<ref name=\"Bradford Observer 2jul1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Opening of new schools at Farsley |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18690702/029/0004 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=2 July 1869 |page=4 col.1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Sculpture is as yet unexamined)\n* Christ Church, [[Windhill and Wrose|Windhill]], Shipley, 1868\u20131869.<ref name=\"Brad DT 17 Aug 1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of Christ Church, Windhill |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000629/18690817/029/0002 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Daily Telegraph |location= |date=17 August 1869 |page=2 col4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The sculpture is as yet unexamined)\n* Former Church of St Silas, [[Hunslet]], 1868\u20131869.<ref name=\"YP & LI 26 Nov 1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of St Silas' Church, Hunslet |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000686/18691126/038/0004 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=26 November 1869 |page=4 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Church of St John the Evangelist, [[Dewsbury]], 1869.<ref name=\"Dewsbury Rep 11 Dec 1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Dewsbury - The re-opening of St John's Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0001541/18691211/081/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Dewsbury Reporter |location= |date=11 December 1869 |page=5 col2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The sculpture is as yet unexamined, but Ingle may have contributed to the pulpit and font)\n* Former Church of All Saints, [[Woodlesford]], 1869-1870.<ref name=\"Leeds Merc 2 Apr 1869\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Laying the foundation stone of a new church at Woodlesford |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000076/18690402/016/0004 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Mercury |location= |date=2 April 1869 |page=4 col4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Sculpture as yet unexamined. However Ingle died in 1870 after two years' severe illness, so his contribution is unknown)\n\n<center><gallery>\nAlbert Memorial at Queensbury (1).JPG|Panel with swan hidden in foliage (1863) on the Albert Memorial, Queensbury\nFile:Frog on 30 Park Place Leeds 363 (9b).jpg|Hidden frog (1865) on 30 Park Place, Leeds\nHoly Trinity Low Moor (7).JPG|Comical albatross nest on pinnacle (1866) on memorial tablet, Holy Trinity, Low Moor\nBradford Commercial Bank 002.jpg|Imaginary creature (1868) on Old Commercial Bank, Bradford\n</gallery></center>\n\n{{Commons category inline|Mawer and Ingle}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Robert Mawer]]\n* [[Catherine Mawer]]\n* [[Charles Mawer]]\n* [[Benjamin Payler]]\n* [[Matthew Taylor (sculptor)]]\n* [[Benjamin Burstall]]\n* [[Mawer and Ingle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Commons category|William Ingle}}\n{{Commons category|Mawer (architectural sculptors)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ingle, William}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1870 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male sculptors]]\n[[Category:People from the Borough of Harrogate]]\n[[Category:Mawer Group]]\n[[Category:Culture in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:History of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Artists from Leeds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = William Ingle\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = St James Boroughbridge (105).JPG\n| image_size       = 250px\n| alt              = William Ingle aged about 24 years, by Robert Mawer\n| caption          = Portrait of William Ingle aged about 24 years, by Robert Mawer, in St James' Church, [[Boroughbridge]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different than name -->\n| birth_date       = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living artists, {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} for dead. For living people supply only the year unless the exact date is already WIDELY published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. Treat such cases as if only the year is known, so use {{birth year and age|YYYY}} or a similar option. --> 1828\n| birth_place      = [[Bishop Thornton]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|1870|03|25|1828|MM|DD}} --> 25 March 1870, aged 41 years\n| death_place      = [[Leeds]]\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = British\n| residence        = 38 Portland Crescent, Leeds\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = Architectural sculpture on:<br />[[Mill Hill Chapel]], 1848<br />Moorlands House, Leeds, 1854<br />[[Leeds Town Hall]], 1854<br />30 Park Place, Leeds, 1865<br />[[Endcliffe Hall]], [[Sheffield]], 1865<br />Commercial Bank, [[Bradford]], 1868\n| style            = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]<br />[[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]]\n| movement         = [[Aesthetic movement]]<br />[[Romanticism]]<br />[[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]]<br>[[Neoclassicism]]\n| spouse           = Ann Elizabeth Agar\n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           = \n}}\n\n'''William Ingle''' (1828 - 25 March 1870) was an architectural sculptor in [[Leeds, West Yorkshire]], England. He specialised in delicately undercut bas relief and small stand-alone stone sculptures of natural and imaginary flora and fauna on churches and on civic, commercial and domestic buildings. He was apprenticed to his uncle [[Robert Mawer]]. After Mawer's death in 1854 he worked in partnership with his aunt [[Catherine Mawer]] and his cousin [[Charles Mawer]] in the company [[Mawer and Ingle]]. Notable works by Ingle exist on [[Leeds Town Hall]], [[Endcliffe Hall]], [[Sheffield]] and Moorlands House, Leeds. He sometimes exhibited gentle humour in his ecclesiastical work, such as faces peering through greenery, and mischievous humour on secular buildings, such as comic rabbits and frogs among foliage. He died of [[tuberculosis]] at age 41 years, having suffered the disease for two years.\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:William Ingle parents (1).jpg|thumb|right|Gravestone of Ingle's parents]]\nWilliam Ingle (1828 - 25 March 1870)<ref name=\"W.Ingle death cert\" >{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=IQsMp7Felj7V%2B2HV%2BWDvWA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=23 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Mar 1870 Ingle William 41 Leeds vol9b p359. The certificate says: 26 March 1870, 73 Portland Crescent, William Ingle, male, 41 years, Phthisis 2 years, certified, Ann Agar of 27 St James St Leeds present at the death.</ref> was the nephew of Robert and Catherine Mawer, and cousin of their son Charles Mawer.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 31 Mar 1855\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The nobility, clergy and gentry |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000336/18550331/052/0001 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Times |location= |date=31 March 1855 |page=1 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> He was the eldest son of Robert Ingle (1799 \u2013 2 August 1860), a corn miller at [[List of mills in North Yorkshire#Bishop Thornton|Render Mills, Bishop Thornton]], and Elizabeth Ingle nee Mawer (1802 \u2013 18 November 1845), sister of the sculptor Robert Mawer.<ref>United Kingdom Census 1841: HO/107/1351/5/10 p.14, Bishop Thornton, Render Mills</ref> Robert Ingle and Elizabeth Mawer were married at Ripon Cathedral on 3 October 1825. They were both buried at Bishop Thornton. William Ingle was baptised on 30 June 1828 at [[Bishop Thornton]], [[North Yorkshire]].<ref>England, Births and Christenings, 1538-1975. Salt Lake City, Utah: FamilySearch, 2013</ref>\n\n===Apprenticeship===\nAssuming the regular pattern of apprenticeship between the ages of 14 and 21 years, Ingle was apprenticed to Robert Mawer between about 1842 and 1849.<ref name=\"Leeds Times 31 Mar 1855\" />\n\n===Family life and career===\n[[File:Old Commercial Bank Bradford 065a.jpg|thumb|right|Portrait of William Ingle aged about 39 years, after contracting [[Tuberculosis|TB]], carved by Catherine Mawer. The feather in his cap celebrates his successful work on the Commercial Bank, [[Bradford]]]]\nHe married Ann Elizabeth Agar (b. 1832 at Kimpton, Yorkshire), daughter of Benjamin Agar, an estate agent, in 1852 at Leeds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=ROSFVCHUYgJNs3TSvwY14Q&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=23 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Marriages Jun 1852, Agar Ann Elizabeth and Ingle William, Leeds vol9b p287</ref> In 1851, at age 22, he was living at a lodging house in Leeds, describing himself as a stone and wood carver.<ref>United Kingdom Census 1851: H.O.107/2321/25 Leeds, 4 Bentick Street</ref> By 1861 he and his wife were living at 38 Portland Crescent, Leeds, and William described himself as a sculptor and stone carver in the Census that year. They had four children: Amelia Jane (b.1852),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=GFPX%2F0rJUYitZaq5Nlsrbg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1852 Ingle Amelia Jane Leeds vol9b p359, (She married in 1874 and/or 1881)</ref> Arthur Robert (1855-1865),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=rt67OXC8IsUi8itUwIwMVQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Mar 1865 Ingle Arthur Robert Leeds vol9b p350</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=dDmDUPyFaGbqU4aDwBR5RQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1855 Ingle Arthur Robert Leeds vol9b p350</ref> Fred (1861-1875),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=6pajAr8cirfs4YBgKC3ECw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1861 Ingle Fred Leeds vol9b p370</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=PKa4GR5ZTPpxTFp5Am6PQg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Jun 1875 Ingle Fred 13 Leeds vol9b p328</ref> and Ernest (1866-1955),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=MySY1WkiD4Rqx%2FUeeYj2Hg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Births Dec 1866 Ingle Ernest Leeds vol9b p444</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=VG4sbQGfBzgibpQHKOGvhw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=25 October 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}} Deaths Mar 1955 Ingle Ernest 88 Wharfedale vol2d p789</ref> all born in Leeds. Ernest was described in the 1871 Census as \"deaf and dumb from birth.\"<ref>United Kingdom Census 1861: RG9/3394 p16 Leeds Portland Crescent.</ref><ref name=\"1871 Census Agar\" >United Kingdom Census 1871: RG10/4566/ West Leeds, 55 St James Street</ref>\n\nIngle was a member of the Mawer Group, a closely-associated group of architectural sculptors working in Leeds in the 19th century. The group included Robert Mawer, Catherine Mawer, Charles Mawer, Benjamin Payler, Matthew Taylor, and Ingle himself. Unlike the other sculptors in this group, Ingle was never credited by personal name for his work, by contemporary newspapers and other documents; they always referred to the company Mawer and Ingle. He was employed as a sculptor by master sculptor Robert Mawer from about 1849 until Robert Mawer's death in 1854, when Ingle became a master sculptor himself. So long as Ingle was working from the Mawer stoneyard, it produced various carving styles including finely undercut natural vegetation, and natural and comical wildlife and mythical animals. After he died, such natural, realistic elements were no longer produced in the same delicate style, so it is reasonable to suppose that this was Ingle's work. Ingle superintended the stone yard and onsite works under the management of Catherine Mawer after Robert Mawer's death,<ref name=\"Leeds Times 31 Mar 1855\" /> then became a partner in the firm of Mawer & Ingle.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Deaths |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000686/18700402/169/0012 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencee |location= |date=2 April 1870 |page=12 |access-date=13 March 2019}} \"Ingle, March 25 1870, aged 41, Mr William Ingle, of the firm of Messrs Mawer & Ingle, stone carvers, Great George Street, Leeds.\"</ref>\n\n[[Architecture of Leeds#Leeds Civic Trust|Leeds Civic Trust]] arranged to unveil two [[blue plaque]]s At the [[Henry Moore Foundation|Henry Moore Institute]] on 11 July 2019, commemorating the work of Robert Mawer, Catherine Mawer and William Ingle, besides the Mawer Group as a whole. This plaques were to be affixed to Moorlands House, Albion Street, and 30 Park Place, both in Leeds, at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinson |first=Andrew HUTC |title=Blue plaques to honour Leeds architectural sculptors who left their mark on some of city's most iconic buildings |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/people/blue-plaques-to-honour-leeds-architectural-sculptors-who-left-their-mark-on-some-of-city-s-most-iconic-buildings-1-9863859 |via= |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location= |date=8 July 2019 |page= |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nWilliam Ingle died aged 41 years on 26 March 1870, at 73 Portland Crescent, Leeds.  He had had [[tuberculosis]] for two years. His mother in law Ann Agar was present at his death.<ref name=\"W.Ingle death cert\" />\n\n==Blue plaque in Leeds==\n[[File:Mawer Group of sculptors blue plaque (4).jpg|thumb|right|Blue plaque for William Ingle]]\nAt the [[Henry Moore Foundation|Henry Moore Institute]] on 11 July 2019, [[Architecture of Leeds#Leeds Civic Trust|Leeds Civic Trust]] unveiled two [[blue plaque]]s in recognition of the Mawer Group. One of them commemorates the work of William Ingle on 30 Park Place, Leeds. It was scheduled to be affixed to the building at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hinson |first=Andrew HUTC |title=Blue plaques to honour Leeds architectural sculptors who left their mark on some of city's most iconic buildings|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/people/blue-plaques-to-honour-leeds-architectural-sculptors-who-left-their-mark-on-some-of-city-s-most-iconic-buildings-1-9863859 |via= |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds, West Yorkshire, England |date=8 July 2019 |page= |access-date=9 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Drysdal |first=Laura |title=A trailblazer for Barbara Hepworth - this is why 'forgotten' sculptor Catherine Mawer has been recognised with a blue plaque in Leeds |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/retro/a-trailblazer-for-barbara-hepworth-this-is-why-forgotten-sculptor-catherine-mawer-has-been-recognised-with-a-blue-plaque-in-leeds-1-9872620 |via= |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |location=Leeds, West Yorkshire, England |date=12 July 2019 |page= |access-date=12 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Works for Robert Mawer==\n{{main|Robert Mawer}}\n\n[[File:Moorlands House Leeds (4).JPG|thumb|right|Sheep's head symbolising the Fleece, or Leeds' source of income (1855) by William Ingle, on Moorlands House]]\n* Church of St Paul and St Jude, [[Manningham, Bradford|Manningham]], 1846\u22121848.<ref name=\"BO 28 Sep 1848 Memorial of SP\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Memorial of St Paul' Church, Manningham |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18480928/021/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=28 September 1848 |page=6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Animal drain-pipe gargoyles.\n* [[Mill Hill Chapel|Mill Hill Unitarian Chapel]], Leeds, 1847-1848.<ref name=\"Preston Chronicle 30 Dec 1848\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New Unitarian Chapel at Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000099/18481230/013/0003 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Preston Chronicle |location= |date=30 December 1848 |page=3 |access-date=13 March 2019}} \"Mawer\" mis-spelled as \"Macor\"</ref> Animal cornice reliefs, fauna and vegetation on reredos, drain-pipe gargoyles, animal and vegetation on pulpit.\n* Church of St Matthew, Bankfoot, [[City of Bradford|Bradford]], 1848\u20131849.<ref name=\"bradford Observer 11dec1849\" >{{cite news|last=From |first=a correspondent  |title=The Church of St Matthew Bankfoot in the parish of Bradford Yorkshire |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18491213/024/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=13 December 1849 |page=6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Vegetation on capitals, drain-pipe gargoyles\n* [[St Michael and All Angels Church, Shelf, West Yorkshire|St Michael and All Angels, Shelf]], Halifax, 1849\u20131850.<ref name=\"Morning Post 24jun1850\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the Church of st Michael and All Angels |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18500624/004/0002 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Morning Post |location= |date=24 June 1850 |page=2 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (No work by Ingle yet identified)\n* St Mary the Virgin, [[Quarry Hill, Leeds]], restoration 1850.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the Church of St. Mary the Virgin, Gomersal |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18510405/040/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=5 April 1851 |page=8, col.3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* Church of St Mary the Virgin, [[Gomersal]], 1850-1851.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 1feb1851\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Church of St Mary the Virgin, Little Gomersal, near Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18510201/056/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=1 February 1851 |page=8 col4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving is as yet unexamined)\n* St Catherine, [[Barmby Moor]], restoration 1851\u22121852.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 17 Apr 1852\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The re-opening of St Catherine's Church, Barmby Moor |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18520417/037/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=17 April 1852 |page=7 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving is as yet unexamined)\n* Church of St James, [[Boroughbridge]], 1851\u22121852.<ref name=\"Yorks Gazette 31 Jul 1852\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of the new church at Boroughbridge |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000266/18520731/023/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archives |newspaper=Yorkshire Gazette |location= |date=31 July 1852 |page=6 col.1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (No carving by Ingle yet found)\n* [[St George's Hall, Bradford]], 1849-1853.<ref name=\"Bradford Observer 1 Sep 1853 opening\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Opening of st George's Hall. Description of the hall |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18530901/027/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=1 September 1853 |page=6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Vine leaves with grapes, Corinthian capitals.\n* Former St Andrew, Listerhills Road, [[City of Bradford|North Horton]], 1853.<ref name=\"Bradford Observer 29 Sep 1853\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of t Andrew's Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18530929/021/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=29 September 1853 |page=5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* St Mark, [[Woodhouse, Leeds]], 1853 and 1856.<ref name=\"LI 5 Nov 1853 font\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=St Marks Church, Woodhouse |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18531105/014/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=5 November 1853 |page=5 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Some tower gargoyles may be Ingle's work\n* Old Church of St John the Evangelist, [[New Wortley]], Leeds, 1853.<ref name=\"LI 19 Nov 1853 consecration\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of St John's Church, New Wortley |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18531119/038/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive|newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=19 November 1853 |page=8 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"LI 25 Nov 1865 reredos\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=New Wortley Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18651125/018/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=25 November 1865 |page=5, col.4 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (Demolished)\n* [[St Matthias' Church, Burley|Church of St Matthias, Burley]], Leeds, 1853\u22121854.<ref name=\"LI 11 Nov 1854 consecration\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of Burley Church, near Leeds |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18541111/039/0008 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=11 November 1854 |page=8 col.5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> (The carving has not yet been examined)\n* Moorlands House, 48 Albion Street, [[Leeds, West Yorkshire|Leeds]], 1852-1855.<ref name=\"LI 17 March 1855 Moorlands\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Leeds and Yorkshire Assurance Company |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18550317/019/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=17 March 1855 |page=5 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Bulls' and sheep's heads, acanthus leaf panels.\n* St Cuthbert, [[Ackworth, West Yorkshire|Ackworth]], 1855.<ref name=\"LI 1 Sep 1855\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Second day's proceedings |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18550901/027/0007 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=1 September 1855 |page=7 col3 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Possibly some foliage decoration, and a dog in foliage on a capital.\n* Reredos at [[Bradford Cathedral|Bradford Parish Church]], 1854\u22121855.<ref>{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The Parish Church |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000155/18550823/036/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Bradford Observer |location= |date=23 August 1855 |page=5 col.6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Foliage on former reredos (since demolished)\n\n{{Commons category inline|Robert Mawer}}\n\n==Works for Catherine Mawer==\n{{main|Catherine Mawer}}\n\n[[File:St Peter Barton upon Humber 2017 (68).JPG|thumb|right|Capital (1859), in faux [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] style, featuring green man-animal among natural foliage, in St Peter, Barton upon Humber]]\n* Susannah Blesard monument, St Mark, [[Woodhouse, Leeds|Woodhouse]], 1856.<ref name=\"LI 18 Oct 1856 tomb\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=The late Mrs Blesard |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18561018/066/0005 |via=British Newspaper Archive|newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=18 October 1856 |page=5 col.2 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Flora and fauna on memorial. \n* Former St Mark's, Low Moor, [[City of Bradford|Bradford]], 1855\u22121857.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 14mar1857\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Consecration of St Mark's Church, Low Moor, near Bradford |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18570314/051/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive|newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=14 March 1857 |page=6 col6 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Foliage on capitals, tympanum of south porch, drainpipe gargoyle, foliage on interior capitals, pulpit and font (interior no longer accessible to public)\n* New Hall for [[Halifax, West Yorkshire|Halifax]] Mechanics Institution, 1855\u22121857.<ref name=\"Leeds Intelligencer 17jan1857\" >{{cite news|last= |first= |title=Halifax Mechanics Institution, inauguration of the new building |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000193/18570117/035/0006 |via=British Newspaper Archive |newspaper=Leeds Intelligencer |location= |date=17 January 1857 |page=6 col1 |access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref> Most of the foliage is by Ingle, while Catherine carved the heads.\n* Church of the Holy Innocents, [[Thornhill Lees]] 1858.<ref name=\"LI 26 Jun 1858 consecration\" >{{cite news|last= |first= 