{"title_page": "K-1 Attack", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Products|date=November 2012}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=November 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = K1 Attack vr EMS.jpg\n| name = K-1 Attack Roadster\n| manufacturer = [[K-1 Engineering]], now [[B-Racing]]\n| production = 2002&ndash;present\n| assembly = [[Bratislava]], [[Slovakia]]\n| class = [[Sports car]]\n| body_style = 2-seat [[Roadster (automobile)|roadster]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| platform = \n| engine = Ford Mondeo ST220 3.0&nbsp;L [[V6 engine|V6]]\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2440|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4040|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1860|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1095|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|992|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| related = \n| designer = Juraj Mitra\n}}\n\nThe ''' K-1 Attack Roadster''' is a [[sports car]] built by the [[Slovakia|Slovak]] car company [[K-1 Engineering]]. The cars are manufactured by hand in [[Bratislava]]. Attack was officially launched in May 2002,<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/supertest-k1-roadster-694330.html Autobild.de web site - Angriff ist die beste Verteidigung (german)]</ref> but was in development since 1999. The car was originally made for racing, developed by Engineer Dick Kvetnansky and designed by Juraj Mitra and was completed in 2000. The car was built initially as a race car, upon seeing the demand as a road car the car was made available as a kit car using the 90-93 Honda Accord as the donor car. Small modifications could be made to accommodate the H22 engine from the Honda Prelude as well.\n\n==History==\nIn May 2002, K-1 Engineering presented the Attack Roadster at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show]] (IAA - International Automobile Exhibition).<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/vorstellung-attack-von-k1-43867.html Autobild.de web site - Attacke auf Elise (german)]</ref> Powered by a mid-mounted 3.0 L (2 967 ccm) Ford Mondeo ST220<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/vorstellung-attack-von-k1-43867.html Autobild.de web site - Attacke auf Elise (german)]</ref> V6 engine, producing 242 PS (178&nbsp;hp) at 7000 rpm, mated to a 6-speed manual transmission gearbox sending power to the rear wheels. The Attack could accelerate to 62&nbsp;mph (100&nbsp;km/h) in 5.2 seconds.<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/supertest-k1-roadster-694330.html Autobild.de web site - Angriff ist die beste Verteidigung (german)]</ref> Top speed was electronically limited to 155.4&nbsp;mph (250&nbsp;km/h).\n\nIn 2003 a K-1 Attack was donated by Mr. Dick Kvetnansky to a development team of high school students in the west Philadelphia Learning Academy and was the only Attack with a full carbon fiber body. The team of students was led by the Engineer-teacher Simon Hauger, their ultimate goal was to build \"The World's first Hybrid Supercar\".  In 2004, the project was completed and won an International fuel efficiency competition in 2005, beating out Billion dollar car manufacturers like Honda, Toyota and even Tesla. In 2006 it again competed and won, sweeping the competition. The car was capable of a 0 - 60 mph time in 3.5 seconds, and gave a mileage up to 68 miles per gallon. The rear wheels of the car were powered by a Volkswagen GTI Diesel engine that was modified to run on soybean oil and there were plans to power the front wheels by an AC Propulsion electric motor and then later by an Azure motor but this was never completed. The car was not only super-fast and economical, but was also eco-friendly (pollution free), thereby achieving its goal. According to the fuel efficiency competition, the car was given a wide media coverage by TV channels like the Discovery Channel, ABC, NBC, CABLE TV, and various  car magazines. The car is now located in Beverly Hills and owned by Prince Fuad Abdallah Haboud Camanero Faresi .\n\nIn 2008, a K-1 Attack was modified by car racer Aljosa Tushek from Slovenia, who got the body modified by Oliver Ashley he also added a luxury interior and an Audi 4.2 liter V8 engine from the Audi RS series delivering {{Convert|450|hp|0|abbr=on}} at 7900 rpm and {{Convert|315|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at just 3,200 rpm. Tushek called it the \"Renovatio T500 Tushek\". It debuted at the Top Marques Monaco in April 2012 and then at the Salon Prive, UK in September 2012. There was also a production version by Ford, available only in Europe.\n\nSomewhere between 20 and 40 were produced and exported to the United States by K-1 Engineering before production ceased. The kit was plagued by poor support, lack of assembly instructions and an extremely difficult build process due to ill-conceived design aspects. In 2011 B-Racing was born and gained the rights and tooling to begin manufacturing again.  Since then countless improvements, refinements and available upgrades have been made including several options for using different donor cars. Pricing has also dropped from the original $20K to less than $10K making the kit very affordable.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:K1 Attack.jpg| K1 Attack at the IAA 2003\nFile:K1 Attack cockpit.jpg|Attack cockpit\nFile:Attack K1 Innenraum.JPG|Attack cockpit 2\nFile:Asanti Attack K1 - Flickr - exfordy (1).jpg| Attack back-view\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.b-racing.cz/en B-Racing current manufacturer of K1 Attack kit cars]\n* [http://www.topspeed.com/cars/prototypes/k-1-attack-roadster-ar35882.html  K-1 Attack Roadster Video at the topspeed.com]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qxr4xjZ1T8s  The World's 1st Hybrid Supercar built on a K-1 Attack base]\n* [http://www.attackforums.com  K1 Attack Forum]\n\n{{Automotive industry in Slovakia}}\n\n[[Category:Roadsters]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Cars of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Products|date=November 2012}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=November 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| image = K1 Attack vr EMS.jpg\n| name = K-1 Attack Roadster\n| manufacturer = [[K-1 Engineering]], now [[B-Racing]]\n| production = 2002&ndash;present\n| assembly = [[Bratislava]], [[Slovakia]]\n| class = [[Sports car]]\n| body_style = 2-seat [[Roadster (automobile)|Roadster]]\n| layout = [[Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| platform = \n| engine = Ford Mondeo ST220 3.0&nbsp;L [[V6 engine|V6]]\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2440|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4040|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1860|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1095|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|992|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| related = \n| designer = Juraj Mitra\n}}\n\nThe ''' K-1 Attack Roadster''' is a [[sports car]] built by the [[Slovakia|Slovak]] car company [[K-1 Engineering]]. The cars are manufactured by hand in [[Bratislava]]. Attack was officially launched in May 2002,<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/supertest-k1-roadster-694330.html Autobild.de web site - Angriff ist die beste Verteidigung (german)]</ref> but was in development since 1999. The car was originally made for racing, developed by Engineer Dick Kvetnansky and designed by Juraj Mitra and was completed in 2000. The car was built initially as a race car, upon seeing the demand as a road car the car was made available as a kit car using the 90-93 Honda Accord as the donor car. Small modifications could be made to accommodate the H22 engine from the Honda Prelude as well.\n\n==History==\nIn May 2002, K-1 Engineering presented the Attack Roadster at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show]] (IAA - International Automobile Exhibition).<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/vorstellung-attack-von-k1-43867.html Autobild.de web site - Attacke auf Elise (german)]</ref> Powered by a mid-mounted 3.0 L (2 967 ccm) Ford Mondeo ST220<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/vorstellung-attack-von-k1-43867.html Autobild.de web site - Attacke auf Elise (german)]</ref> V6 engine, producing 242 PS (178&nbsp;hp) at 7000 rpm, mated to a 6-speed manual transmission gearbox sending power to the rear wheels. The Attack could accelerate to 62&nbsp;mph (100&nbsp;km/h) in 5.2 seconds.<ref>[http://www.autobild.de/artikel/supertest-k1-roadster-694330.html Autobild.de web site - Angriff ist die beste Verteidigung (german)]</ref> Top speed was electronically limited to 155.4&nbsp;mph (250&nbsp;km/h).\n\nIn 2003 a K-1 Attack was donated by Mr. Dick Kvetnansky to a development team of high school students in the west Philadelphia Learning Academy and was the only Attack with a full carbon fiber body. The team of students was led by the Engineer-teacher Simon Hauger, their ultimate goal was to build \"The World's first Hybrid Supercar\".  In 2004, the project was completed and won an International fuel efficiency competition in 2005, beating out Billion dollar car manufacturers like Honda, Toyota and even Tesla. In 2006 it again competed and won, sweeping the competition. The car was capable of a 0 - 60 mph time in 3.5 seconds, and gave a mileage up to 68 miles per gallon. The rear wheels of the car were powered by a Volkswagen GTI Diesel engine that was modified to run on soybean oil and there were plans to power the front wheels by an AC Propulsion electric motor and then later by an Azure motor but this was never completed. The car was not only super-fast and economical, but was also eco-friendly (pollution free), thereby achieving its goal. According to the fuel efficiency competition, the car was given a wide media coverage by TV channels like the Discovery Channel, ABC, NBC, CABLE TV, and various  car magazines. The car is now located in Beverly Hills and owned by Prince Fuad Abdallah Haboud Camanero Faresi .\n\nIn 2008, a K-1 Attack was modified by car racer Aljosa Tushek from Slovenia, who got the body modified by Oliver Ashley he also added a luxury interior and an Audi 4.2 liter V8 engine from the Audi RS series delivering {{Convert|450|hp|0|abbr=on}} at 7900 rpm and {{Convert|315|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at just 3,200 rpm. Tushek called it the \"Renovatio T500 Tushek\". It debuted at the Top Marques Monaco in April 2012 and then at the Salon Prive, UK in September 2012. There was also a production version by Ford, available only in Europe.\n\nSomewhere between 20 and 40 were produced and exported to the United States by K-1 Engineering before production ceased. The kit was plagued by poor support, lack of assembly instructions and an extremely difficult build process due to ill-conceived design aspects. In 2011 B-Racing was born and gained the rights and tooling to begin manufacturing again.  Since then countless improvements, refinements and available upgrades have been made including several options for using different donor cars. Pricing has also dropped from the original $20K to less than $10K making the kit very affordable.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:K1 Attack.jpg| K1 Attack at the IAA 2003\nFile:K1 Attack cockpit.jpg|Attack cockpit\nFile:Attack K1 Innenraum.JPG|Attack cockpit 2\nFile:Asanti Attack K1 - Flickr - exfordy (1).jpg| Attack back-view\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.b-racing.cz/en B-Racing current manufacturer of K1 Attack kit cars]\n* [http://www.topspeed.com/cars/prototypes/k-1-attack-roadster-ar35882.html  K-1 Attack Roadster Video at the topspeed.com]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qxr4xjZ1T8s  The World's 1st Hybrid Supercar built on a K-1 Attack base]\n* [http://www.attackforums.com  K1 Attack Forum]\n\n{{Automotive industry in Slovakia}}\n\n[[Category:Roadsters]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2002]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Cars of Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-1_Attack"}
{"title_page": "Andr\u00e9s Palop", "text_new": "{{spanish name|Palop|Cervera}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Andr\u00e9s Palop\n| image = AndresPalop.jpg\n| caption = Palop playing for [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in 2008\n| fullname = Andr\u00e9s Palop Cervera<ref name=Profile>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/132/388.html|title=Andr\u00e9s PALOP Cervera|publisher=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1973|10|22|df=y}}<ref name=Profile/>\n| birth_place = [[L'Alc\u00fadia]], Spain\n| height = 1.84 m<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20131997 | clubs1 = [[Valencia CF Mestalla|Valencia B]] | caps1 = 68 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1997\u20132005 | clubs2 = [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] | caps2 = 43 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1997\u20131999 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] (loan) | caps3 = 74 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2005\u20132013 | clubs4 = [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] | caps4 = 217 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2013\u20132014 | clubs5 = [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] | caps5 = 0 | goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps = 402 | totalgoals = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2015\u20132016 | managerclubs1 = [[CD Alcoyano|Alcoyano]]\n| manageryears2 = 2018\u20132019 | managerclubs2 = [[UD Ibiza|Ibiza]]\n}}\n'''Andr\u00e9s Palop Cervera''' ({{IPA-va|an\u02c8d\u027ees pa\u02c8lob}}; born 22 October 1973) is a Spanish former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\nAfter having languished on the bench of hometown club [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] for most of his stay,<ref name=ED>{{cite news|url=http://www.estadiodeportivo.com/sevilla/2013/02/02/quiniela-palop-caben-variantes/136.html|title=En la quiniela de Palop no caben las variantes|trans-title=No variables in Palop's pools|publisher=[[Estadio Deportivo]]|language=Spanish|date=2 February 2013|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> he became a premiere player with [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] well into his 30s, helping it consolidate in both the domestic and [[UEFA|European]] fronts. Over 15 seasons, he appeared in 295 matches in [[La Liga]], where he also represented [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399]].\n\nPalop was selected by [[Spain national football team|Spain]] for [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], but never earned an international [[Cap (sport)|cap]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\n====Valencia====\nBorn in [[L'Alc\u00fadia]], [[Valencian Community]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.farodevigo.es/deportes/2014/04/21/palop-anuncia-retirada/1008718.html|title=Palop anuncia su retirada|trans-title=Palop announces his retirement|publisher=[[Faro de Vigo]]|language=Spanish|date=21 April 2014|accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref> Palop was a youth product of local giants [[Valencia CF]], and his first professional seasons were spent at neighbours [[Villarreal CF]], in a two-year loan spell. He was the undisputed starter in both the side's [[La Liga]] [[1997\u201398 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|promotion in 1998 \u2013 a first ever]] \u2013 and [[1998\u201399 La Liga|relegation the following season]], being subsequently recalled by the ''Che''.\n\nIn his six-year stint with Valencia's main squad, however, Palop was mostly backup to veteran [[Santiago Ca\u00f1izares]], his most games consisting of 15 in [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|his first year]]. As the club were crowned league champions in [[2001\u201302 La Liga|2002]] and [[2003\u201304 La Liga|2004]], he could only appear seven times combined (all in the former campaign), and eventually grew unsettled.<ref name=ED/>\n[[File:Palop.jpg|thumb|Palop during a match with [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] in 2013]]\n\n====Sevilla====\nPalop joined [[Sevilla FC]] in summer 2005, quickly becoming one of the [[Andalusia]]ns' cornerstones as they added five titles in only one year. On 15 March 2007, he made headlines when he scored an [[Association football#Duration and tie-breaking methods|injury time]]-equalising goal in the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] [[Single-elimination tournament|round-of-16]] tie against [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk]], forcing [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] as a result \u2013 Sevilla, which had drawn 2\u20132 at home in the first leg, went on to win 3\u20132, and eventually [[2006\u201307 UEFA Cup|won the competition]] for the second consecutive time;<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/fixturesresults/round=2367/match=300520/report=rp.html Sevilla saved by last gasp Palop]; UEFA, 15 March 2007</ref><ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=214763&cc=5739 Shakhtar Donetsk 2\u20133 FC Sevilla]; [[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]], 15 March 2007</ref> in [[2007 UEFA Cup Final|the final]] against fellow league team [[RCD Espanyol]] he stopped three of four [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]s in [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|the shootout]], being named [[Man of the match]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070521181541/http://www.uefa.com/competitions/uefacup/fixturesresults/round%3D2370/match%3D300100/report%3Drp.html Palop ensures cup joy for Sevilla]; UEFA, 16 May 2007</ref>\n\nIn the following campaigns, veteran Palop continued to be an undisputed starter for Sevilla, never appearing in fewer than 31 league matches. In [[2009\u201310 La Liga|2009\u201310]] he helped to a fourth place in the league, with the subsequent [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|qualification]] to the [[UEFA Champions League]], and [[2009\u201310 Copa del Rey|victory]] in the [[Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://deportes.elpais.com/deportes/2010/05/19/actualidad/1274253740_850215.html|title=Gan\u00f3 el serio, cay\u00f3 el alegre|trans-title=Serious won, playful lost|publisher=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|language=Spanish|date=19 May 2010|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Bayer Leverkusen====\nIn early June 2013, Palop signed a one-year contract with [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen]], moving abroad for the first time at the age of nearly 40.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1958942.html Palop adds experience to Leverkusen]; UEFA, 2 June 2013</ref> He was used exclusively as back-up by the German [[Bundesliga]] club, and in April 2014 he announced his retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://es.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ger/news/newsid=2093642.html|title=Palop cuelga los guantes|trans-title=Palop hangs up gloves|publisher=UEFA|language=Spanish|date=21 April 2014|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nPalop was first called up for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in August 2007, for a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] with [[Greece national football team|Greece]], after a last-minute injury to [[Iker Casillas]].<ref>[http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/seleccion/es/desarrollo/1027583.html Casillas no viajar\u00e1 a Grecia y Luis llama a Palop (Casillas will not travel to Greece and Luis calls Palop)]; Marca, 20 August 2007 (in Spanish)</ref> However, he did not leave the bench in the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2007/08/21/futbol/1187704369.html|title=Luis confirma a Reina: 'Palop ya tendr\u00e1 tiempo de jugar'|trans-title=Luis confirms Reina: 'Palop's time to play will come'|publisher=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=21 August 2007|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Cap (sport)|Uncapped]], Palop lost a narrow competition with [[Pepe Reina]] of [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] for second-choice at [[UEFA Euro 2008]], but beat [[FC Barcelona]]'s [[V\u00edctor Vald\u00e9s]] for the third spot on the squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sevilla.eldesmarque.com/sevilla-futbol-club/26184--sp-7554421|title=Palop ir\u00e1 a la Eurocopa|trans-title=Palop will go to the Eurocup|publisher=El Desmarque|language=Spanish|date=25 March 2008|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2008/05/17/mas_futbol/1210975201_850215.html|title=Ra\u00fal se queda fuera; Sergio Garc\u00eda y Cazorla son las novedades|trans-title=Ra\u00fal is ousted; Sergio Garc\u00eda and Cazorla are the novelties|publisher=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=17 May 2008|accessdate=15 June 2016}}</ref> During the ceremony following Spain's victory in the tournament, he wore [[Luis Arconada]]'s original [[UEFA Euro 1984|Euro 1984]] final shirt. He received the gold medal from [[Michel Platini]] (who had won the 1984 continental competition, scoring the final opener from an Arconada blunder), later president of [[UEFA]].<ref>[http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20080702/arconada-alucino-con-el-gesto-de-palop_53493140694.html Arconada alucin\u00f3 con el gesto de Palop (Arconada went crazy with Palop's gesture)]; Mundo Deportivo, 2 July 2008 (in Spanish)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sefutbol.com/en/euro-2008-palops-tribute-legendary-goalkeeper-arconada|title=Euro 2008: Palop's tribute to a legendary goalkeeper (Arconada)|publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]]|language=Spanish|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=15 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624165932/http://www.sefutbol.com/en/euro-2008-palops-tribute-legendary-goalkeeper-arconada|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nOn 18 February 2015, Palop was named manager at [[CD Alcoyano]] for the remainder of [[2014\u201315 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|the season]] in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]].<ref>[http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20150218/futbol/carlos-sempere-entrenara-al-alcoyano-y-andres-palop-sera-su-ayudante_54426297903.html Carlos Sempere entrenar\u00e1 al Alcoyano y Andr\u00e9s Palop ser\u00e1 su ayudante (Carlos Sempere will manage Alcoyano and Andr\u00e9s Palop will be his assistant)]; [[Mundo Deportivo]], 18 February 2015 (in Spanish)</ref><ref>[http://www.marca.com/2015/02/18/futbol/mas_futbol/1424274093.html Palop afrontar\u00e1 en el Alcoyano su primera experiencia como entrenador (Palop will his face his first experience as a manager at Alcoyano)]; [[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]], 18 February 2015 (in Spanish)</ref> In June, after achieving the sufficient qualifications, he took the post on a permanent basis,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sevilla.abc.es/deportes/orgullodenervion/noticias/sevilla-fc/palop-ya-es-el-nuevo-entrenador-del-alcoyano-cumplo-un-sueno-84159-1433431681.html|title=Palop ya es el nuevo entrenador del Alcoyano: \"Hago realidad un sue\u00f1o\"|trans-title=Palop is now Alcoyano's new manager: \u201cI've made a dream come true\u201d|publisher=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref> announcing his exit in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/20160507/401638331741/palop-anuncia-que-no-seguira-el-ano-proximo-como-entrenador-del-alcoyano.html|title=Palop anuncia que no seguir\u00e1 el a\u00f1o pr\u00f3ximo como entrenador del Alcoyano|trans-title=Palop announces that he will not continue next year as manager of Alcoyano|publisher=Mundo Deportivo|language=Spanish|date=7 May 2016|accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nPalop was appointed as the new head coach of [[UD Ibiza]] on 27 September 2018, with that club also competing in the third level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibizaud.com/comunicado-oficial-andres-palop/|title=Andr\u00e9s Palop, nuevo entrenador de la UD Ibiza|trans-title=Andr\u00e9s Palop, new UD Ibiza manager|publisher=UD Ibiza|language=Spanish|date=27 September 2018|accessdate=2 October 2018}}</ref> He was dismissed the following 25 February after winning ten of his 21 games, leaving the team eight points from a playoff place.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/abci-segunda-ibiza-destituye-andres-palop-como-entrenador-201902251635_noticia.html|title=El Ibiza destituye a Andr\u00e9s Palop como entrenador|trans-title=Ibiza dismiss Andr\u00e9s Palop as manager|publisher=ABC|language=Spanish|date=25 February 2019|accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nPalop was mainly known for his shot-stopping abilities, and also earned a reputation as a penalty-saving specialist throughout his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/live-scores/news/y=2007/m=11/news=the-long-shadow-zamora-637303.html|title=The long shadow of Zamora|publisher=FIFA|date=13 November 2007|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club statistics==\n:Sources:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j164.html|title=Palop: Andr\u00e9s Palop Cervera|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/andres-palop-cervera/3115/|title=Palop|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.andres.palop.4119.en.html|title=Andr\u00e9s Palop|publisher=Footballdatabase|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup<ref group=lower-alpha>Includes [[Copa del Rey]] and [[DFB-Pokal]] matches.</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Valencia CF|Valencia]] \n|[[1997\u201398 La Liga|1997\u201398]]\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[La Liga]]\n|0||0||0||0||-||-||-||-||0||0\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 La Liga|1999\u201300]]\n|15||0||0||0||6<ref group=lower-alpha name=UCL>Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]</ref>||0||-||-||21||0\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301]]\n|1||0||2||0||1<ref group=lower-alpha name=UCL/>||0||-||-||4||0\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 La Liga|2001\u201302]]\n|7||0||0||0||3<ref group=lower-alpha name=UEL>Appearances 