{"title_page": "Interstate 805", "text_new": "{{short description|Interstate highway in California}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=CA\n|type=I\n|route=805\n|section=621\n|spur_type=I\n|spur_of=5\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|frame-lat=32.726|frame-long=-117.130|zoom=9|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 805}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-805 highlighted in red\n|alternate_name=Jacob Dekema Freeway\n|length_mi=28.016\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"trucklist\"/>\n|established=1959<ref name=\"yr1959\" />\n|direction_a=South\n|counties=[[San Diego County, California|San Diego]]\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=CA|I|5}} in [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|905}} in [[Otay Mesa, San Diego|Otay Mesa]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|54}} in [[National City, California|National City]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|94}} in [[San Diego]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|15}} in San Diego\n*{{jct|state=CA|I|8}} in [[Mission Valley, San Diego|Mission Valley]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|163}} in [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|52}} in [[University City, San Diego|University City]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=CA|I|5}} in [[Sorrento Valley, San Diego|Sorrento Valley]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=780\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=880\n}}\n'''Interstate 805''' ('''I-805''') is a major north\u2013south [[List of auxiliary Interstate Highways|auxiliary Interstate Highway]] in [[Southern California]]. It is a [[bypass (road)|bypass]] auxiliary route of [[Interstate 5 in California|I-5]], running roughly through the center of the [[San Diego\u2013Tijuana metropolitan area|Greater San Diego region]] from [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]] (part of the city of [[San Diego]]) near the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexico\u2013U.S. border]] to near [[Del Mar, California|Del Mar]]. The southern terminus of I-805 at I-5 in San Ysidro is less than a mile north of the Mexican border. I-805 then traverses the cities of [[Chula Vista, California|Chula Vista]] and [[National City, California|National City]] before reentering San Diego. The freeway passes through the San Diego neighborhoods of [[North Park, San Diego|North Park]], [[Mission Valley, San Diego|Mission Valley]], [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont]], and [[University City, San Diego|University City]] before terminating at I-5 in the [[Sorrento Valley, San Diego|Sorrento Valley]] neighborhood near the Del Mar city limit.\n\nPlanning for I-805 began in 1956, and the route was officially designated in 1959 before it was renumbered in the [[1964 state highway renumbering (California)|1964 state highway renumbering]]. Starting in 1967, the freeway was built in phases, with the northern part of the freeway finished before the southern part. I-805 was completed and open to traffic in 1975. Named the '''Jacob Dekema Freeway''' after the longtime head of the regional division of the [[California Department of Transportation]] (Caltrans), I-805 has been frequently cited for its complex engineering and architecture, including near I-8 on the '''Mission Valley Viaduct'''. Since then, several construction projects have taken place, including the construction of local and express lanes at the northern interchange with I-5. [[High-occupancy toll]] lanes are under construction on both the northern and southern portions of the route.\n\n==Route description==\n[[File:I-805 Northbound at CA 905.jpg|thumb|left|I-805 northbound at SR&nbsp;905]]\nThe route begins at [[Interstate 5 in California|I-5]] near the Mexican border in a far south part of [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]], a neighborhood of [[San Diego]]. As it starts its journey northward, it quickly has a junction with [[California State Route 905|State Route&nbsp;905]] (SR&nbsp;905) before exiting the city of San Diego and entering [[Chula Vista, California|Chula Vista]].<ref name=\"gmaps\" /> Within the past 20&nbsp;years the freeway has delineated the apparent divide between rich and poor in the city of Chula Vista; those on the eastern side of the freeway have been more affluent and have better schools compared to those on the western side.<ref>{{cite news | title=A City Divided\u2014by Interstate 805\u2014Chula Vista, and Its Schools, Face Serious Threat of East Versus West | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=February 7, 2004 | author=Moran, Chris | page=B1|oclc=25257675}}</ref> Just outside the city, I-805 meets [[County Route S17 (California)|County Route S17]] (CR&nbsp;S17), also named Bonita Road, before coming to an interchange with [[California State Route 54|SR&nbsp;54]]. The freeway then enters [[National City, California|National City]], where it intersects Sweetwater Road and Plaza Boulevard, before leaving the city and reentering the city of San Diego.<ref name=\"gmaps\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/?ll=32.775729,-117.03186&spn=0.587715,1.215363&t=m&z=10|title=I-805|accessdate=September 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nI-805 continues northward through San Diego, where it intersects [[California State Route 94|SR&nbsp;94]], the Martin Luther King Jr. Freeway. As the freeway continues through downtown San Diego, it meets [[California State Route 15|SR&nbsp;15]], the continuation of [[Interstate 15|I-15]]. It then intersects [[El Cajon Boulevard]] before passing under the Hazard Memorial Bridge that carries Adams Avenue.<ref name=\"gmaps\" /> The bridge was named after Roscoe Hazard for his involvement in the construction of several roads and highways in [[Southern California]]. I-805 then travels on the Mission Valley Viaduct, a towering [[reinforced concrete|reinforced]] [[concrete viaduct]] built in 1972, spanning over [[Mission Valley, San Diego|Mission Valley]] and the [[San Diego River]].<ref name=\"Caltrans\">{{CA Named Freeways | pages=85, 212, 225}}</ref> The viaduct is the top stack of the Jack Schrade Interchange over [[Interstate 8|I-8]], which runs along the south side of Mission Valley and crosses underneath the viaduct perpendicularly, and is San Diego County's only symmetrical [[stack interchange]]. The [[San Diego Trolley]] traffic also runs under the viaduct on the valley floor.<ref name=\"gmaps\" />\n\n[[File:Interstate 805-5 Split.jpg|thumb|right|The beginning of I-805 south at I-5 during the evening rush hour]]\nAfter intersecting [[California State Route 163|SR&nbsp;163]], also known as the Cabrillo Freeway, I-805 continues through suburban San Diego, where it meets [[California State Route 52|SR&nbsp;52]] in [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont Mesa]]. North of SR&nbsp;52, it closely parallels I-5 near [[La Jolla]], heading northwest. Passing under the Eastgate Mall arch bridge and entering [[Sorrento Valley, San Diego|Sorrento Valley]], it finally meets its north end at I-5.<ref name=\"gmaps\" /> During the widening project which was completed in 2007, I-5 at the I-805 merge was built to be 21&nbsp;lanes wide.<ref name=\"newlanes\">{{cite news | url=http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20070328/news_1mi28merge.html | title=Four New Southbound Lanes at I-5/805 Merge Set to Open | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=March 28, 2007 | accessdate=September 13, 2013 | author=Schmidt, Steve | page=NC1 | oclc=25257675 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111063936/http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20070328/news_1mi28merge.html | archivedate=November 11, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Eastbound [[California State Route 56|SR&nbsp;56]] and Carmel Mountain Road are accessible via a parallel [[carriageway]] for local traffic heading northbound from I-805; traffic from SR&nbsp;56 westbound can merge onto I-805 from the local bypass.<ref name=\"gmaps\" />\n\nThe route is officially known as the Jacob Dekema Freeway after Jacob Dekema, a pioneering force from the [[California Department of Transportation]] (Caltrans) who helped shape the San Diego freeway system.<ref name=\"Caltrans\" /> It is also part of the [[California Freeway and Expressway System]]<ref name=\"cafes\">{{CAFESystem}}</ref> and the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=fhwa-nhs>{{FHWA NHS map|region=sandiego}}</ref> a network of highways that are considered essential to the country's economy, defense, and mobility by the [[Federal Highway Administration]].<ref name=NHS-FHWA>{{FHWA NHS}}</ref> In 2013, I-805 had an [[annual average daily traffic]] (AADT) of 41,500 at the southern terminus, and 262,000 between Bonita Road and SR 54, the latter of which was the highest AADT for the highway.<ref name=traffic>{{Caltrans traffic|year=2013|start=505|end=980}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Construction===\nAccording to Dekema, planning for I-805 began in 1956.<ref name=\"breaking\">{{cite news | title=Ceremonies Open Work on Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 26, 1967 | page=C1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The original routing for I-805 was approved as an Interstate Highway in July 1958.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/tsip/hseb/products/state_highway_routes_selected_information_1995_revised.pdf |format= PDF  |title= State Highway Routes: Selected Information |publisher= California Department of Transportation |year= 1995 |page= 350}}</ref> It was added to the state highway system and the Freeway and Expressway System in 1959 as Route&nbsp;241.<ref name=\"yr1959\">{{cite CAstat|year=1959|ch=1062}}</ref> I-805 was expected to reduce traffic on what was then US&nbsp;101 between Los Angeles and San Diego, when the former was opened.<ref>{{cite news | title=U.S. 101 Ranked Among Deadliest | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 14, 1962 | page=A36|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Route&nbsp;241 was renumbered to Route&nbsp;805 in the [[1964 state highway renumbering (California)|1964 state highway renumbering]], and I-5 was designated along the route from Los Angeles to San Diego.<ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1963|ch=385|p=1177}}</ref> Further planning was underway in 1965, with the goal to have the route built by 1972, the federal highway funding deadline.<ref>{{cite news | title=150 Additional Freeway Miles Scheduled for San Diego Area | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 21, 1965 | author=Parry, Bill | page=A31|oclc=13155544}}</ref> This was to be the first freeway in the area with no prior road along its route that it would replace; the goal was to provide a bypass around San Diego for those traveling to Mexico, and improve access for local residents. By June, houses along the route in the [[North Park, San Diego|North Park]] area were being sold, as the land was needed for the first stretch of the freeway to be constructed.<ref>{{cite news | title=Route 805 Hailed as 'Totally New' | work=The San Diego Union | date=June 6, 1965 | author=Parry, Bill | page=A13|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The next year, Dekema confirmed that the first portion of what was known as the Inland Freeway to be built would be between Home and Adams avenues.<ref>{{cite news | title=Dekema Predicts Completion of Inland Freeway by 1972 | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 3, 1966 | author=James, Paul | page=B4|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1967, [[Construction bidding|bidding]] began, after construction had been delayed by that of the I-5 and I-8 freeways, both of which had been given higher priority. This first portion would run from Wabash Boulevard to around Madison Avenue (a distance of {{convert|3.5|mi|km|disp=or}}), and the next portion would include the I-8 interchange.<ref>{{cite news | title=State Asks Bids for Freeway In E. San Diego | work=The San Diego Union | date=May 23, 1967 | author=Ross, Charles | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The R.E. Hazard and W.F. Maxwell Companies won the low bid of $11.7&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|11700000|1967|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{Inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) in mid-1967.<ref>{{cite news | title=S.D. Firms' Bid OKd for Freeway Job | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 23, 1967 | page=C7|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The groundbreaking ceremony happened on September 25 at El Cajon Boulevard and Boundary Street.<ref name=\"breaking\" /> In August 1968, the portion of I-805 from just south of I-8 to north of Friars Road, including the interchange with I-8, was put up for bidding; at a budgeted $27.5&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|27500000|1968|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), it was the most expensive job that the Division of Highways had ever put up for bid.<ref>{{cite news | title=$27.1 Million Freeway Job Set for Bids | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 27, 1968 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The winning bid was $20.9&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|29400000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), and was awarded to R.E. Hazard Contracting Company and W.F. Maxwell Company.<ref>{{cite news | title=2 Area Firms Win Interchange Job | work=The San Diego Union | date=November 8, 1968 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aerial - Interstate 805 in San Diego, CA 01.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of I-805 near the SR 15 interchange]]\nConstruction had begun on the viaduct by May 1969;<ref>{{cite news | title=New Mission Valley Span Beauty Cited | work=The San Diego Union | date=May 27, 1969 | author=Stone, Joe | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> in the meantime, National City was making plans for developing the freeway corridor with motels and restaurants, as well as a shopping center.<ref>{{cite news | title=National City Flexes Muscles for Growth | work=The San Diego Union | date=June 14, 1969 | page=B7|oclc=13155544}}</ref> In mid-1969, bidding was to begin on {{convert|3.2|mi|km}} of I-805 from north of Friars Road to north of what was then [[U.S. Route 395 in California|US 395]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Called for Section of Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 5, 1969 | page=C8|oclc=13155544}}</ref> which would become SR&nbsp;163.<ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1969|ch=294}}</ref> Construction from J Street south to near San Ysidro was underway by September, when there were concerns that an order from President [[Richard Nixon]] to reduce federal construction projects by 75&nbsp;percent might affect funding for the portion north of Friars Road. However, Governor [[Ronald Reagan]] lifted the associated freeze in construction at the state level a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite news | title=San Diego Freeway Work Hit by Action | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 5, 1969 | page=A8|oclc=13155544}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Construction OKd on Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 17, 1969 | author=Clance, Homer | page=A1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> A month later, the contract for the portion between Friars Road and US&nbsp;395 had been awarded for $15&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|15000000|1969|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}); the portions between there and north of Miramar Road were in the planning phases, while construction continued south of I-8 to Wabash Boulevard.<ref>{{cite news | title=$15 Million Pact Let for Freeways | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 9, 1969 | author=Scott-Blair, Michael | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The {{convert|2.4|mi|km|adj=on}} portion from SR&nbsp;52 to Miramar Road had been contracted out to O.G. Sansome Company for $5.6&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|5600000|1969|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) by the end of 1969.<ref>{{cite news | title=Riverside Firm Wins Contract for Road Work | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 21, 1969 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Meanwhile, $4&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|4000000|1969|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) of state funding was spent in 1969 to find housing for those who were to be displaced by the freeway in San Ysidro.<ref>{{cite news | title=San Ysidro's Replacement Homes Studied | work=The San Diego Union | date=November 8, 1969 | page=B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nBy March 1970, the original section between Home Avenue and near I-8 was almost finished. The Mission Valley portion extending north of US&nbsp;395, as well as from Otay Valley Road and J Street in Chula Vista, were still under construction.<ref>{{cite news | title=Highway Office Reports on Area Freeway Progress | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 15, 1970 | page=B4|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The portion immediately north of US&nbsp;395 was contracted to A.A. Baxter Corporation, E.C. Young, and Young and Sons, Inc. for $7.9&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news | title=Highway Pact Awarded | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 19, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|7900000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). On July 6, the first section to begin construction was dedicated, and was to be opened from El Cajon Boulevard to Wabash Boulevard soon thereafter; the rest of the section would not open until the Mission Valley interchange with I-8 was finished.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Link Dedicated | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 7, 1970 |  page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nA second border crossing in the San Ysidro area was proposed near the [[Playas de Tijuana]] area, that would be accessible from I-805, although another alternative was considered near [[Brown Field Municipal Airport|Brown Field]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Border Entry Urged Near [[Brown Field Municipal Airport|Brown Field]] | work=The San Diego Union | date=May 15, 1970 |  page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> A formal study on the matter was commissioned in August.<ref>{{cite news | title=City Council Airs New 805 Route | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 26, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> However, this would have added $10&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|10000000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) to the cost of the freeway, and possibly delay it by up to 10&nbsp;years; furthermore, most traffic crossing the border was found to head to [[Tijuana]] and not [[Ensenada, Baja California|Ensenada]].<ref>{{cite news | title=$10 Million Loss Seen in 805 Rerouting | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 1, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Following this, the city of Chula Vista asked that the state proceed with the original plans to construct the freeway, even though it would pass through a San Ysidro neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news | title=Chula Vista Urges Early Road Work | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 10, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1970, bidding began for the final portion of the northern half of I-805 between Miramar Road and I-5;<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Sought for 805 Link | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 24, 1970 | page=B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref> a month later, the segments between Home Avenue and SR&nbsp;94, and SR&nbsp;54 to 12th Street had funding allocated.<ref>{{cite news | title=State Highway Commission Adopts $905 Million Budget | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 23, 1970 | page=B9|oclc=13155544}}</ref> By the end of the year, Hazard, Maxwell, and Matich had submitted the low bid of around $7.2&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|7200000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) for the northernmost portion.<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Taken by State on 2 Highways | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 17, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The Chula Vista portion of the freeway from Main Street to L&nbsp;Street was completed in February 1971; by then, the estimated date for completing the entire freeway had slipped to 1975 from 1972.<ref>{{cite news | title=Dedication Set for Part of Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 25, 1971 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> By March, the projected completion date for the Mission Valley bridge was revised to July 1972.<ref>{{cite news | title=Gap Closed on Mission Valley Bridge | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 16, 1971 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> A 102-home [[mobile home park]] was approved by the City Council a few weeks later to house those who were displaced by the freeway construction.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mobile Home Park Readied in San Ysidro | work=The San Diego Union | date=April 9, 1971 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nThe portion of the freeway from Otay Valley Road to Telegraph Canyon Road opened during 1972.<ref name=\"band\">{{cite news | title=Completion Date Fixed in August | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 19, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> On October 22, several unconstructed portions of I-805 were partially funded, including from Chula Vista south past [[California State Route 75|SR&nbsp;75]], north of the completed Chula Vista portion to SR&nbsp;54, from SR&nbsp;54 to Plaza Boulevard in National City, from there to SR&nbsp;94 (including the interchange with [[SR&nbsp;252 (CA)|SR&nbsp;252]]), and from there to Home Avenue.<ref>{{cite news | title=$60 Million Due County for Roads | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 23, 1971 | pages=B1, B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Before the end of the year, the portion from SR&nbsp;94 to Home Avenue entered the bidding phase;<ref>{{cite news | title=State Asks Bids on Section of Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 15, 1971 | page=D4|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Guy F. Atkinson Company won the contract for roughly $9.96&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|9960000|1972|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) in early 1972.<ref>{{cite news | title=Long Beach Firm Awarded Contract | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 26, 1972 | page=B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Following a request from the El Cajon City Council,<ref>{{cite news | title=El Cajon Council to Ask Cycling on Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 2, 1972 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> March 19 was set aside as a Community Cycle Day for bicyclists to travel the newly finished freeway from El Cajon Boulevard to SR&nbsp;52, just before the freeway was to be dedicated the next day;<ref>{{cite news | title=Route 805 Bicycle Day Set March 19 | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 8, 1972 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> the entire Mission Valley Viaduct was open to traffic that month.<ref name=\"band\" />\n\nBy the beginning of 1974, I-805 was open north of Home Avenue, and from Otay Valley Road to Telegraph Canyon Road in Chula Vista;<ref name=\"band\" /> five segments remaining were under construction, and the last segment was funded.<ref>{{cite news | title=Public's Mood Shifts away from Freeways | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 8, 1974 | page=X16|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The Imperial Avenue section of I-805 remained in the budget, despite revisions in response to the [[1973 oil crisis]].<ref>{{cite news | title=County Road Share Set at $30 Million | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 12, 1974 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> In late January, I-805 between SR&nbsp;15 and SR&nbsp;94 was opened to traffic, though not all of the ramps at the SR&nbsp;94 interchange were operational.<ref>{{cite news | title=New Highway Link to Open | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 28, 1974 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The connectors to SR&nbsp;94 east were completed in March.<ref>{{cite news | title=805 Open to State 94 | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 7, 1974 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The entire portion between SR&nbsp;94 and Home Avenue cost $10.5&nbsp;million<ref name=\"band\" /> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|10500000|1974|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). Construction between SR&nbsp;94 and Imperial Avenue was well under way by December, at a cost of $8.5&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Continues Southward Advance | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 13, 1974 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|8500000|1974|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}).\n\nAs the scheduled completion of the freeway neared, Mayor Tom Hamilton of Chula Vista expressed concerns regarding the predicted development of the I-805 corridor, and the decisions that the City Council would need to make regarding such plans.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mayor Foresees Scramble for Sites as I-805 Develops | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 12, 1975 | author=Scaglione, Cecil | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The portion south of Otay Valley Road cost $15&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|15000000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), and the portion between Telegraph Canyon Road and Sweetwater Road cost&nbsp;$12 million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|12000000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). The portion from there to Imperial Avenue was projected to cost $10.2&nbsp;million<ref name=\"band\" /> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|10200000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). The dedication of the freeway took place on July 23, 1975, even though the freeway was not entirely finished, due to the desire to hold the ceremony during the summer.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Dedicated but Opening Date Delayed | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 24, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> I-805 from Plaza Boulevard to Telegraph Canyon Road opened to traffic on July 28, leaving the freeway complete except for the portion between Plaza Boulevard and SR&nbsp;94. While portions of the freeway were nearly ready for traffic, there were reports of motorists driving on the closed freeway, which the [[California Highway Patrol]] warned was illegal.<ref>{{cite news | title=Unopened 805 Usage Prohibited | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 29, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> On September 3, Dekema announced that the entirety of the freeway would open the next day as he made a final inspection of the unopened portion; the total cost of the construction was $145&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|145000000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). However, Dekema announced that there was no more state funding available to construct further roads for the short-term.<ref>{{cite news | title=Officials Say Interstate 805 Is End of Road for Funds | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 4, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition, artwork, and architecture===\n[[Image:Miramar op 805.jpg|thumb|left|The La Jolla Village Drive overpass on I-805 northbound, with the Eastgate Mall bridge in the background]]\nThe Mission Valley Viaduct was recognized by the [[American Society of Civil Engineers]] (ASCE) as the \"Outstanding Civil Engineering Project for 1973 in the San Diego Area\"; it was designed to match the close by [[Mission San Diego de Alcal\u00e1]] with its columns that look similar to cathedral windows,<ref name=\"spectrum\" /> and arch-like shapes etched into the textured concrete. The viaduct was designed to span {{convert|3900|ft|m}}, and use squared-off support columns instead of traditional cylindrical supports. Octagonal columns were to be used on the ramps and the ends of the bridge.<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Due Soon for Viaduct in Mission Valley | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 11, 1968 | author=Smith, Cliff | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Over 600&nbsp;tons of steel bars were to be used,<ref>{{cite news | title=Viaduct Takes Shape | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 7, 1969 | page=A28|oclc=13155544}}</ref> and the bridge was constructed as high as {{convert|98|ft|m}} above I-8.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Span Shows Geometric Beauty | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 24, 1970 | page=A3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The Adams Avenue Bridge over I-805 was also recognized for its {{convert|439|ft|m|adj=on}} span and two tapered supports on the ends of the bridge; in 1968, a [[Princeton University]] engineering professor asked for a copy of the design from Caltrans for educational purposes.<ref name=\"spectrum\">{{cite news | title=Bridges Span Design Spectrum | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 11, 1976 | page=F6|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The construction supervisor, in fact, compared the construction of this bridge to building a boat, and it was constructed from the middle outward rather than the conventional method of building from the ends inward. The span was designed to be {{convert|268|ft|m}} long,<ref>{{cite news | title=Boat-Like Curves Mark Overpass | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 11, 1968 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> and {{convert|100|ft|m}} high.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Bridge Grows in Beauty | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 29, 1969 | page=A3|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nAwards for the Eastgate Mall (or Old Miramar Bridge) came from the [[Federal Highway Administration]], San Diego Highway Development Association, and Prestressed Concrete Institute Awards Program; at the time, it was one of the first arch bridges in the state, and did not use traditional concrete pillars.<ref name=\"spectrum\" /> The ''San Diego Union'' (predecessor to the ''Union-Tribune'') published a few freelance articles in 1984 about I-805, complimenting the four-level interchange with I-8 and the [[arch bridge]] at Eastgate Mall, while mentioning that subsequent inflation after their completion would have made such structures more difficult to build if they had been constructed later. Other artwork and architecture that was mentioned included the Wateridge development in Sorrento Valley, and the \"Stargazer\" building by Alexander Liberman that was lit with fluorescent colors at night.<ref>{{cite news | title=Outdoor Artworks Bring New Beauty to Freeway Travel | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 16, 1984 | author=Lewinson, David | page=E8|oclc=13155544}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Architecture at Its Best in S.D Freeways | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 26, 1984 | author=Jones, Bob | page=F1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nHowever, not all forms of artwork along the highway were uncontroversial. In 1977, there were several complaints regarding new billboards that were installed at the northern terminus of the highway, since they blocked the view of the coast.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ruling Awaited on New Billboards On Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 30, 1977 | author=Ball, Neil | page=B16|oclc=13155544}}</ref> In 1981, an illegal mural that was determined to be incomplete was discovered at the I-8 interchange; while Caltrans discouraged the painting of such murals, they were impressed with the portion that had already been completed.<ref>{{cite news | title=I-805 Graffiti Artist Sought | work=The San Diego Union | date=April 2, 1981 | author=Gross, Greg | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Art Cole, the artist, stepped forward to the department, and was allowed to finish the mural of a desert highland sunrise; following this, Caltrans made efforts to have other murals commissioned.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mural Is Given to San Diego | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 28, 1981 | page=B13|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nThe San Ysidro Chamber of Commerce attempted to have I-805 named as the San Ysidro Freeway in 1976.<ref>{{cite news | title=Border Community Wants I-805 Named San Ysidro | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 16, 1976 | author=Scaglione, Cecil | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> However, I-805 was named after Jacob Dekema in August 1981, and ceremonies to mark the occasion occurred in February 1982.<ref name=\"dekema\">{{cite news | title=Father Of S.D. Freeways Now Has One of His Own | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 20, 1982 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The plaque honoring Dekema was installed in November at the Governor Drive interchange.<ref>{{cite news | title=Dekema Honored | work=The San Diego Union | date=November 23, 1982 | author=Romero, Bill | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Because of his efforts in designing I-805, Ed Settle of Caltrans was given the Outstanding Civil Engineering Award from the ASCE; he designed several other regional freeways, including SR&nbsp;163 through [[Balboa Park (San Diego)|Balboa Park]] and I-5 through San Diego.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ed Settle: Designer Created Scenic Freeway in Balboa Park | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=April 3, 2005 | author=Williams, Jack | page=J5|oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\n[[File:Interstate 5 and Interstate 805 Sorrento Valley interchange.jpg|thumb|\"Dual freeway\" at northern I-805 terminus]]\nThe construction of a \"dual freeway\" at the northern end of I-805 was discussed as early as 1989, referring to the two [[carriageways]] needed for each direction of the freeway, resulting in four total. It would require drivers to use the new local lanes to access eastbound SR&nbsp;56 from I-5 or I-805. The project would allow for trucks to use the new lanes to assist in merging with traffic. However, it faced opposition from local residents, concerned about the loss of the view from their homes, as well as environmentalists concerned about nearby wetlands.<ref>{{cite news | title=Bottleneck at I-5/805 Is Dilemma | work=The San Diego Union | date=April 30, 1989 | author=Weisberg, Lori | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Further objections espoused the view that the congestion would continue to increase, regardless of what was done, and that the new road would be at capacity in a few years.<ref>{{cite news | title=Residents Express Anguish at Plans to Expand I-5 Junction | work=Evening Tribune | date=June 2, 1989 | author=Kubik, Agnes | location=San Diego | page=B8|oclc=37687666}}</ref> The San Diego Association of Governments (SANDAG) funded the construction with $110 million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|110000000|2000|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) in mid-2000.<ref>{{cite news | title=Highways Receive Bulk of Money in SANDAG Transportation Plan | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=July 22, 2000 | author=Arner, Mark | page=B3|oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the \"dual freeway\" began in early 2002, at a cost of $182&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news | title=I-5/805 Merge Widening Under Way | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=March 1, 2002 | last=LaRue | first=Steve | page=B2| oclc=25257675}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|182000000|2002|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). The northbound lanes were scheduled to open in February 2006.<ref>{{cite news | title=Showers Push Back Opening of Bypass | work=The San Diego Union-Tribune | date=February 19, 2006 | page=B3| oclc=25257675}}</ref> The southbound lanes were completed in early 2007.<ref name=\"newlanes\" /> That year, a three-year project began to allow [[Driverless car|robot controlled vehicles]], including buses and trucks, to use a special lane.  The intention is to allow the vehicles to travel at shorter following distances and thereby allow more vehicles to use the lanes.  The vehicles will still have drivers since they need to enter and exit the special lanes. The system was designed by Swoop Technology, based in San Diego County.<ref name=\"RoboBus\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/cars/futuretransport/magazine/15-08/st_robot | title=Robot Buses Pull In to San Diego's Fastest Lane | work=Wired | date=July 24, 2007 | accessdate=August 19, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110112944/http://www.wired.com/cars/futuretransport/magazine/15-08/st_robot|archivedate=November 10, 2012 |oclc=24479723}}</ref>\n\nTwo years later, construction began on two auxiliary lanes on I-805 southbound from SR&nbsp;54 to Bonita Road, to improve traffic flow at the SR&nbsp;54 interchange.<ref>{{cite news | title=Short Takes | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=October 13, 2009 | author=Schmidt, Steve | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> In 2010, Caltrans proposed adding [[high-occupancy toll]] express lanes between SR&nbsp;15 and East Palomar Street in Chula Vista.<ref>{{cite news | title=Public Hearings Set on I-805 Expansion | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=September 21, 2010 | author=Fry, Wendy | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> The California Transportation Commission (CTC) awarded $100&nbsp;million for the work in June 2011, which would be split into two phases at the interchange with SR&nbsp;54.<ref>{{cite news | title=I-805 HOV-Lane Project Gets $100M from State | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=June 30, 2011 | author=Hawkins, Robert | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> Work is also underway to add two [[High-occupancy vehicle|HOV lanes]] between SR&nbsp;52 and Mira Mesa Boulevard; this project also received $59.5&nbsp;million from the CTC in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news | title=State Sending Region $82.6M for Road Work | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=September 19, 2011 | author=Hawkins, Robert | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> Meanwhile, SANDAG made arrangements to purchase the [[SR&nbsp;125 (CA)|SR&nbsp;125]] toll road and reduce the tolls, which was hoped to encourage commuters to take that road instead of I-805 and reduce congestion; this would then enable Caltrans to construct two managed lanes instead of the original four.<ref>{{cite news | title=SANDAG Agrees to Purchase South County Toll Road | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=December 17, 2011 | author=Hawkins, Robert | page=A1|oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, construction began on the northern HOV lanes; the project is expected to cost $86&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news | title=Express Lanes Project to Commence on I-805 | work=U-T San Diego | date=February 26, 2013 | author=Nichols, Chris | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> By May, construction on the Palomar Street direct access ramps had begun, and the Carroll Canyon Road ramps were almost finished.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ramps to Speed Access to I-15 | work=U-T San Diego | date=May 1, 2013 | author=Nichols, Chris | page=NC1|oclc=25257675}}</ref>  The northern project is expected to be complete in 2015,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist11/facts/805ManagedLanesNorth.pdf | format=PDF | title=Interstate 805 Express Lanes North Project Fact Sheet | publisher=California Department of Transportation | author=District 11 | date=June 2013 | accessdate=October 8, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928061742/http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist11/facts/805ManagedLanesNorth.pdf | archivedate=September 28, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> and the southern express lanes opened in March 2014 at a cost of $1.4&nbsp;billion, with an option to expand them into two lanes in each direction, and a proposed direct ramp to the express lanes.<ref>{{cite news | title=I-805 carpool lanes open in So. County | work=U-T San Diego | date=March 5, 2014 | author=Nichols, Chris | url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/mar/05/805-carpool-south-county-chula-vista-national-city/|oclc=25257675}}</ref> A 2012 Caltrans report proposed adding four managed lanes along the entire length of the highway.<ref name=\"TCR2\">{{cite web | author=Staff|url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist11/departments/planning/pdfs/tcs/2012_I_805_TCS.pdf | title=I-5 Transportation Concept Summary| publisher=Caltrans | date=June 2012 | accessdate=June 21, 2014 | format=PDF|pages=17}}</ref> Construction on HOV lanes from SR&nbsp;905 to SR&nbsp;15 began in 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title=Next phase for I-805 needs funding | work=U-T San Diego | date=May 8, 2014 | author=Nichols, Chris | page=NI7 | oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\n==Exit list==\n{{CAinttop|exit|county=San Diego|post_ref=<br><ref name=trucklist /><ref name=traffic /><ref name=bridgelog>{{Caltrans bridgelog}}</ref>|exit_ref=<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=I-805 Northbound Freeway Interchanges |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivenorth.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=California Department of Transportation |work=California Numbered Exit Uniform System |access-date=February 5, 2009 |last=Howe |first=Don |date=August 16, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330012507/http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivenorth.pdf |archivedate= March 30, 2008 |location=Sacramento }}<br />{{cite web |title=I-805 Southbound Freeway Interchanges |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivesouth.pdf |publisher=California Department of Transportation |work=California Numbered Exit Uniform System |access-date=February 5, 2009 |last=Howe |first=Don |date=August 16, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005032518/http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivesouth.pdf |archivedate=October 5, 2009 |format=PDF |location=Sacramento }}</ref>\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=San Ysidro\n|lspan=5\n|postmile=0.15\n|exit=\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|I|5|dir1=south|location1=[[Mexico]] only}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; exit 1A on I-5\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=0.15\n|exit=1A\n|road=Camino de la Plaza\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; last USA exit southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=0.65\n|exit=1B\n|road=San Ysidro Boulevard\n|notes=Signed as exit 1A northbound}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=1.81\n|exit=1C\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|905}}\n|notes=Signed as exit 1B northbound; SR&nbsp;905 exit 2B; future [[Interstate 905|I-905]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=2.90\n|exit=2\n|road=Palm Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Chula Vista\n|lspan=6\n|postmile=3.65\n|exit=3\n|road=Main Street / Auto Park Drive\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=4.42\n|exit=4\n|road=Olympic Parkway / E. Orange Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=hov\n|postmile=none\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=E. Palomar Street\n|notes=HOV access only; southbound left exit and northbound entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=6.06\n|exit=6\n|road=L Street / Telegraph Canyon Road\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=7.16\n|exit=7\n|road=H Street\n|notes=Signed as exits 7A (east) and 7B (west) southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=7.76\n|exit=7C\n|road=E Street / Bonita Road ([[County Route S17 (California)|CR&nbsp;S17]])\n|notes=Northbound exit is part of exit 7.\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=National City\n|lspan=3\n|postmile=8.85\n|exit=8\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|54}}\n|notes=Signed as exit 9 southbound; SR&nbsp;54 exit 2\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=9.05\n|exit=9\n|road=Sweetwater Road\n|notes=Signed as exit 8 southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=10.28\n|exit=10\n|road=Plaza Boulevard\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=San Diego\n|lspan=25\n|postmile=11.31\n|exit=11A\n|road=43rd Street\n|notes=Signed as exit 11B southbound; former [[California State Route 252|SR&nbsp;252]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=R11.36\n|exit=11B\n|road=47th Street / Palm Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[National City, California|National City]]\n|notes=Signed as exit 11A southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=12.34\n|exit=12A\n|road=Imperial Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=12.95\n|exit=12B\n|road=Market Street\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=13.51\n|exit=13A\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|94|dir1=east|name1=M. L. King Jr. Freeway}}\n|notes=Southbound access to SR&nbsp;94 west is via exit 14; SR&nbsp;94 exit 3\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=13.95\n|exit=13B\n|road=Home Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=14.64\n|exit=14\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|15|name1=[[Escondido Freeway]]|SR|94|to2=yes|dir2=west|name2=M. L. King Jr. Freeway}}\n|notes=Future [[Interstate 15 in California|I-15]]; SR&nbsp;15 exit 3\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=15.95\n|exit=15\n|road=North Park Way / University Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=16.43\n|exit=16\n|road={{jctname|state=CA|US-Hist|80|name1=[[El Cajon Boulevard]]|noshield=yes}}\n|notes=Former US&nbsp;80\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=16.99\n|exit=17A\n|road=Adams Avenue / Madison Avenue\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=17.65\n|exit=17B\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|I|8|location1=[[List of beaches in San Diego|Beaches]]|city2=El Centro}}\n|notes=Signed as exit 17 northbound; I-8 exit 6B\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=18.89\n|exit=18\n|road=Murray Ridge Road / Phyllis Place\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=20.23\n|exit=20A\n|road=Mesa College Drive / Kearny Villa Road\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=20.60\n|exit=20B\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|163|name1=[[Cabrillo Freeway]]|dir1=north|city1=Escondido}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; SR&nbsp;163 exit 7A southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=20.60\n|exit=20\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|CA|163|name1=[[Cabrillo Freeway]]|dir1=south|city1=Downtown San Diego}}\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; SR&nbsp;163 exit 7A northbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=21.65\n|exit=21\n|road=Balboa Avenue\n|notes=Former [[California State Route 274|SR&nbsp;274]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=22.56\n|exit=22\n|road=Clairemont Mesa Boulevard\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=23.65\n|exit=23\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|52}}\n|notes=SR&nbsp;52 exit 3\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=24.44\n|exit=24\n|road=Governor Drive\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=25.48\n|exit=25A\n|road=Nobel Drive\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=25.94\n|exit=25B\n|road={{jct|extra=hospital}} Miramar Road / La Jolla Village Drive\n|notes=Serves UC San Diego Health Center}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=hov\n|postmile=none\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=Carroll Canyon Road\n|notes=HOV access only\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=27.07\n|postmile2=28.30\n|exit=27\n|road=Mira Mesa Boulevard / Vista Sorrento Parkway / Sorrento Valley Road\n|notes=Signed as exits 27A (Mira Mesa/Vista Sorrento) and 27B (Sorrento Valley Rd.) northbound; Vista Sorrento Pkwy. not signed southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=28.87\n|pmspan=2\n|exit=33A\n|road={{jct|state=CA|I|5|dir1=north|name1=Local Bypass|to2=to|SR|56|dir2=east}}\n|notes=Northbound exit and southbound entrance; exit number follows I-5\n}}\n{{CAint\n|postmile=none\n|exit=\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|I|5|dir1=north|name1=[[Interstate 5 in California|San Diego Freeway]]|city1=Los Angeles}}\n|notes=Northern terminus; no access to I-5 south\n}}\n{{jctbtm|exit|keys=hov,incomplete}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{portal-inline|California Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n* [http://www.aaroads.com/california/i-805_ca.html I-805] at AARoads.com\n* [http://www.cahighways.org/505-805.html#805 I-805] at California Highways\n* [http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/roadinfo/i805 Route 805 highway conditions] at Caltrans\n\n{{3di|5}}\n\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in California|05-8]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary Interstate Highways|05-8]]\n[[Category:Interstate 5|8 California]]\n[[Category:Southern California freeways|805]]\n[[Category:Roads in San Diego County, California|Interstate 05-8]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Interstate highway in California}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=CA\n|type=I\n|route=805\n|section=621\n|spur_type=I\n|spur_of=5\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|frame-lat=32.726|frame-long=-117.130|zoom=9|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 805}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-805 highlighted in red\n|alternate_name=Jacob Dekema Freeway\n|length_mi=28.016\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"trucklist\"/>\n|established=1959<ref name=\"yr1959\" />\n|direction_a=South\n|counties=[[San Diego County, California|San Diego]]\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=CA|I|5}} in [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]]\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|905}} in [[Otay Mesa, San Diego|Otay Mesa]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|54}} in [[National City, California|National City]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|94}} in [[San Diego]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|15}} in San Diego\n*{{jct|state=CA|I|8}} in [[Mission Valley, San Diego|Mission Valley]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|163}} in [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont]]\n*{{jct|state=CA|SR|52}} in [[University City, San Diego|University City]]\n}}\n|direction_b=North\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=CA|I|5}} in [[Sorrento Valley, San Diego|Sorrento Valley]]\n|previous_type=I\n|previous_route=780\n|next_type=I\n|next_route=880\n}}\n'''Interstate 805''' ('''I-805''') is a major north\u2013south [[List of auxiliary Interstate Highways|auxiliary Interstate Highway]] in [[Southern California]]. It is a [[bypass (road)|bypass]] auxiliary route of [[Interstate 5 in California|I-5]], running roughly through the center of the [[San Diego\u2013Tijuana metropolitan area|Greater San Diego region]] from [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]] (part of the city of [[San Diego]]) near the [[Mexico\u2013United States border|Mexico\u2013U.S. border]] to near [[Del Mar, California|Del Mar]]. The southern terminus of I-805 at I-5 in San Ysidro is less than a mile north of the Mexican border. I-805 then traverses the cities of [[Chula Vista, California|Chula Vista]] and [[National City, California|National City]] before reentering San Diego. The freeway passes through the San Diego neighborhoods of [[North Park, San Diego|North Park]], [[Mission Valley, San Diego|Mission Valley]], [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont]], and [[University City, San Diego|University City]] before terminating at I-5 in the [[Sorrento Valley, San Diego|Sorrento Valley]] neighborhood near the Del Mar city limit.\n\nPlanning for I-805 began in 1956, and the route was officially designated in 1959 before it was renumbered in the [[1964 state highway renumbering (California)|1964 state highway renumbering]]. Starting in 1967, the freeway was built in phases, with the northern part of the freeway finished before the southern part. I-805 was completed and open to traffic in 1975. Named the '''Jacob Dekema Freeway''' after the longtime head of the regional division of the [[California Department of Transportation]] (Caltrans), I-805 has been frequently cited for its complex engineering and architecture, including near I-8 on the '''Mission Valley Viaduct'''. Since then, several construction projects have taken place, including the construction of local and express lanes at the northern interchange with I-5. [[High-occupancy toll]] lanes are under construction on both the northern and southern portions of the route.\n\n==Route description==\n[[File:I-805 Northbound at CA 905.jpg|thumb|left|I-805 northbound at SR&nbsp;905]]\nThe route begins at [[Interstate 5 in California|I-5]] near the Mexican border in a far south part of [[San Ysidro, San Diego|San Ysidro]], a neighborhood of [[San Diego]]. As it starts its journey northward, it quickly has a junction with [[California State Route 905|State Route&nbsp;905]] (SR&nbsp;905) before exiting the city of San Diego and entering [[Chula Vista, California|Chula Vista]].<ref name=\"gmaps\" /> Within the past 20&nbsp;years the freeway has delineated the apparent divide between rich and poor in the city of Chula Vista; those on the eastern side of the freeway have been more affluent and have better schools compared to those on the western side.<ref>{{cite news | title=A City Divided\u2014by Interstate 805\u2014Chula Vista, and Its Schools, Face Serious Threat of East Versus West | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=February 7, 2004 | author=Moran, Chris | page=B1|oclc=25257675}}</ref> Just outside the city, I-805 meets [[County Route S17 (California)|County Route S17]] (CR&nbsp;S17), also named Bonita Road, before coming to an interchange with [[California State Route 54|SR&nbsp;54]]. The freeway then enters [[National City, California|National City]], where it intersects Sweetwater Road and Plaza Boulevard, before leaving the city and reentering the city of San Diego.<ref name=\"gmaps\">{{google maps|url=https://maps.google.com/?ll=32.775729,-117.03186&spn=0.587715,1.215363&t=m&z=10|title=I-805|accessdate=September 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nI-805 continues northward through San Diego, where it intersects [[California State Route 94|SR&nbsp;94]], the Martin Luther King Jr. Freeway. As the freeway continues through downtown San Diego, it meets [[California State Route 15|SR&nbsp;15]], the continuation of [[Interstate 15|I-15]]. It then intersects [[El Cajon Boulevard]] before passing under the Hazard Memorial Bridge that carries Adams Avenue.<ref name=\"gmaps\" /> The bridge was named after Roscoe Hazard for his involvement in the construction of several roads and highways in [[Southern California]]. I-805 then travels on the Mission Valley Viaduct, a towering [[reinforced concrete|reinforced]] [[concrete viaduct]] built in 1972, spanning over [[Mission Valley, San Diego|Mission Valley]] and the [[San Diego River]].<ref name=\"Caltrans\">{{CA Named Freeways | pages=85, 212, 225}}</ref> The viaduct is the top stack of the Jack Schrade Interchange over [[Interstate 8|I-8]], which runs along the south side of Mission Valley and crosses underneath the viaduct perpendicularly, and is San Diego County's only symmetrical [[stack interchange]]. The [[San Diego Trolley]] traffic also runs under the viaduct on the valley floor.<ref name=\"gmaps\" />\n\n[[File:Interstate 805-5 Split.jpg|thumb|right|The beginning of I-805 south at I-5 during the evening rush hour]]\nAfter intersecting [[California State Route 163|SR&nbsp;163]], also known as the Cabrillo Freeway, I-805 continues through suburban San Diego, where it meets [[California State Route 52|SR&nbsp;52]] in [[Clairemont, San Diego|Clairemont Mesa]]. North of SR&nbsp;52, it closely parallels I-5 near [[La Jolla]], heading northwest. Passing under the Eastgate Mall arch bridge and entering [[Sorrento Valley, San Diego|Sorrento Valley]], it finally meets its north end at I-5.<ref name=\"gmaps\" /> During the widening project which was completed in 2007, I-5 at the I-805 merge was built to be 21&nbsp;lanes wide.<ref name=\"newlanes\">{{cite news | url=http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20070328/news_1mi28merge.html | title=Four New Southbound Lanes at I-5/805 Merge Set to Open | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=March 28, 2007 | accessdate=September 13, 2013 | author=Schmidt, Steve | page=NC1 | oclc=25257675 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111063936/http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20070328/news_1mi28merge.html | archivedate=November 11, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Eastbound [[California State Route 56|SR&nbsp;56]] and Carmel Mountain Road are accessible via a parallel [[carriageway]] for local traffic heading northbound from I-805; traffic from SR&nbsp;56 westbound can merge onto I-805 from the local bypass.<ref name=\"gmaps\" />\n\nThe route is officially known as the Jacob Dekema Freeway after Jacob Dekema, a pioneering force from the [[California Department of Transportation]] (Caltrans) who helped shape the San Diego freeway system.<ref name=\"Caltrans\" /> It is also part of the [[California Freeway and Expressway System]]<ref name=\"cafes\">{{CAFESystem}}</ref> and the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]],<ref name=fhwa-nhs>{{FHWA NHS map|region=sandiego}}</ref> a network of highways that are considered essential to the country's economy, defense, and mobility by the [[Federal Highway Administration]].<ref name=NHS-FHWA>{{FHWA NHS}}</ref> In 2013, I-805 had an [[annual average daily traffic]] (AADT) of 41,500 at the southern terminus, and 262,000 between Bonita Road and SR 54, the latter of which was the highest AADT for the highway.<ref name=traffic>{{Caltrans traffic|year=2013|start=505|end=980}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Construction===\nAccording to Dekema, planning for I-805 began in 1956.<ref name=\"breaking\">{{cite news | title=Ceremonies Open Work on Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 26, 1967 | page=C1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The original routing for I-805 was approved as an Interstate Highway in July 1958.<ref>{{cite book |url= http://www.dot.ca.gov/hq/tsip/hseb/products/state_highway_routes_selected_information_1995_revised.pdf |format= PDF  |title= State Highway Routes: Selected Information |publisher= California Department of Transportation |year= 1995 |page= 350}}</ref> It was added to the state highway system and the Freeway and Expressway System in 1959 as Route&nbsp;241.<ref name=\"yr1959\">{{cite CAstat|year=1959|ch=1062}}</ref> I-805 was expected to reduce traffic on what was then US&nbsp;101 between Los Angeles and San Diego, when the former was opened.<ref>{{cite news | title=U.S. 101 Ranked Among Deadliest | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 14, 1962 | page=A36|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Route&nbsp;241 was renumbered to Route&nbsp;805 in the [[1964 state highway renumbering (California)|1964 state highway renumbering]], and I-5 was designated along the route from Los Angeles to San Diego.<ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1963|ch=385|p=1177}}</ref> Further planning was underway in 1965, with the goal to have the route built by 1972, the federal highway funding deadline.<ref>{{cite news | title=150 Additional Freeway Miles Scheduled for San Diego Area | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 21, 1965 | author=Parry, Bill | page=A31|oclc=13155544}}</ref> This was to be the first freeway in the area with no prior road along its route that it would replace; the goal was to provide a bypass around San Diego for those traveling to Mexico, and improve access for local residents. By June, houses along the route in the [[North Park, San Diego|North Park]] area were being sold, as the land was needed for the first stretch of the freeway to be constructed.<ref>{{cite news | title=Route 805 Hailed as 'Totally New' | work=The San Diego Union | date=June 6, 1965 | author=Parry, Bill | page=A13|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The next year, Dekema confirmed that the first portion of what was known as the Inland Freeway to be built would be between Home and Adams avenues.<ref>{{cite news | title=Dekema Predicts Completion of Inland Freeway by 1972 | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 3, 1966 | author=James, Paul | page=B4|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1967, [[Construction bidding|bidding]] began, after construction had been delayed by that of the I-5 and I-8 freeways, both of which had been given higher priority. This first portion would run from Wabash Boulevard to around Madison Avenue (a distance of {{convert|3.5|mi|km|disp=or}}), and the next portion would include the I-8 interchange.<ref>{{cite news | title=State Asks Bids for Freeway In E. San Diego | work=The San Diego Union | date=May 23, 1967 | author=Ross, Charles | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The R.E. Hazard and W.F. Maxwell Companies won the low bid of $11.7&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|11700000|1967|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{Inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) in mid-1967.<ref>{{cite news | title=S.D. Firms' Bid OKd for Freeway Job | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 23, 1967 | page=C7|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The groundbreaking ceremony happened on September 25 at El Cajon Boulevard and Boundary Street.<ref name=\"breaking\" /> In August 1968, the portion of I-805 from just south of I-8 to north of Friars Road, including the interchange with I-8, was put up for bidding; at a budgeted $27.5&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|27500000|1968|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), it was the most expensive job that the Division of Highways had ever put up for bid.<ref>{{cite news | title=$27.1 Million Freeway Job Set for Bids | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 27, 1968 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The winning bid was $20.9&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|29400000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), and was awarded to R.E. Hazard Contracting Company and W.F. Maxwell Company.<ref>{{cite news | title=2 Area Firms Win Interchange Job | work=The San Diego Union | date=November 8, 1968 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aerial - Interstate 805 in San Diego, CA 01.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of I-805 near the SR 15 interchange]]\nConstruction had begun on the viaduct by May 1969;<ref>{{cite news | title=New Mission Valley Span Beauty Cited | work=The San Diego Union | date=May 27, 1969 | author=Stone, Joe | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> in the meantime, National City was making plans for developing the freeway corridor with motels and restaurants, as well as a shopping center.<ref>{{cite news | title=National City Flexes Muscles for Growth | work=The San Diego Union | date=June 14, 1969 | page=B7|oclc=13155544}}</ref> In mid-1969, bidding was to begin on {{convert|3.2|mi|km}} of I-805 from north of Friars Road to north of what was then [[U.S. Route 395 in California|US 395]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Called for Section of Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 5, 1969 | page=C8|oclc=13155544}}</ref> which would become SR&nbsp;163.<ref>{{cite CAstat|year=1969|ch=294}}</ref> Construction from J Street south to near San Ysidro was underway by September, when there were concerns that an order from President [[Richard Nixon]] to reduce federal construction projects by 75&nbsp;percent might affect funding for the portion north of Friars Road. However, Governor [[Ronald Reagan]] lifted the associated freeze in construction at the state level a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite news | title=San Diego Freeway Work Hit by Action | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 5, 1969 | page=A8|oclc=13155544}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Construction OKd on Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 17, 1969 | author=Clance, Homer | page=A1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> A month later, the contract for the portion between Friars Road and US&nbsp;395 had been awarded for $15&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|15000000|1969|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}); the portions between there and north of Miramar Road were in the planning phases, while construction continued south of I-8 to Wabash Boulevard.<ref>{{cite news | title=$15 Million Pact Let for Freeways | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 9, 1969 | author=Scott-Blair, Michael | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The {{convert|2.4|mi|km|adj=on}} portion from SR&nbsp;52 to Miramar Road had been contracted out to O.G. Sansome Company for $5.6&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|5600000|1969|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) by the end of 1969.<ref>{{cite news | title=Riverside Firm Wins Contract for Road Work | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 21, 1969 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Meanwhile, $4&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|4000000|1969|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) of state funding was spent in 1969 to find housing for those who were to be displaced by the freeway in San Ysidro.<ref>{{cite news | title=San Ysidro's Replacement Homes Studied | work=The San Diego Union | date=November 8, 1969 | page=B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nBy March 1970, the original section between Home Avenue and near I-8 was almost finished. The Mission Valley portion extending north of US&nbsp;395, as well as from Otay Valley Road and J Street in Chula Vista, were still under construction.<ref>{{cite news | title=Highway Office Reports on Area Freeway Progress | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 15, 1970 | page=B4|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The portion immediately north of US&nbsp;395 was contracted to A.A. Baxter Corporation, E.C. Young, and Young and Sons, Inc. for $7.9&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news | title=Highway Pact Awarded | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 19, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|7900000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). On July 6, the first section to begin construction was dedicated, and was to be opened from El Cajon Boulevard to Wabash Boulevard soon thereafter; the rest of the section would not open until the Mission Valley interchange with I-8 was finished.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Link Dedicated | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 7, 1970 |  page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nA second border crossing in the San Ysidro area was proposed near the [[Playas de Tijuana]] area, that would be accessible from I-805, although another alternative was considered near [[Brown Field Municipal Airport|Brown Field]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Border Entry Urged Near [[Brown Field Municipal Airport|Brown Field]] | work=The San Diego Union | date=May 15, 1970 |  page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> A formal study on the matter was commissioned in August.<ref>{{cite news | title=City Council Airs New 805 Route | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 26, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> However, this would have added $10&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|10000000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) to the cost of the freeway, and possibly delay it by up to 10&nbsp;years; furthermore, most traffic crossing the border was found to head to [[Tijuana]] and not [[Ensenada, Baja California|Ensenada]].<ref>{{cite news | title=$10 Million Loss Seen in 805 Rerouting | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 1, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Following this, the city of Chula Vista asked that the state proceed with the original plans to construct the freeway, even though it would pass through a San Ysidro neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news | title=Chula Vista Urges Early Road Work | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 10, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1970, bidding began for the final portion of the northern half of I-805 between Miramar Road and I-5;<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Sought for 805 Link | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 24, 1970 | page=B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref> a month later, the segments between Home Avenue and SR&nbsp;94, and SR&nbsp;54 to 12th Street had funding allocated.<ref>{{cite news | title=State Highway Commission Adopts $905 Million Budget | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 23, 1970 | page=B9|oclc=13155544}}</ref> By the end of the year, Hazard, Maxwell, and Matich had submitted the low bid of around $7.2&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|7200000|1970|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) for the northernmost portion.<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Taken by State on 2 Highways | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 17, 1970 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The Chula Vista portion of the freeway from Main Street to L&nbsp;Street was completed in February 1971; by then, the estimated date for completing the entire freeway had slipped to 1975 from 1972.<ref>{{cite news | title=Dedication Set for Part of Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 25, 1971 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> By March, the projected completion date for the Mission Valley bridge was revised to July 1972.<ref>{{cite news | title=Gap Closed on Mission Valley Bridge | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 16, 1971 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> A 102-home [[mobile home park]] was approved by the City Council a few weeks later to house those who were displaced by the freeway construction.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mobile Home Park Readied in San Ysidro | work=The San Diego Union | date=April 9, 1971 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nThe portion of the freeway from Otay Valley Road to Telegraph Canyon Road opened during 1972.<ref name=\"band\">{{cite news | title=Completion Date Fixed in August | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 19, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> On October 22, several unconstructed portions of I-805 were partially funded, including from Chula Vista south past [[California State Route 75|SR&nbsp;75]], north of the completed Chula Vista portion to SR&nbsp;54, from SR&nbsp;54 to Plaza Boulevard in National City, from there to SR&nbsp;94 (including the interchange with [[SR&nbsp;252 (CA)|SR&nbsp;252]]), and from there to Home Avenue.<ref>{{cite news | title=$60 Million Due County for Roads | work=The San Diego Union | date=October 23, 1971 | pages=B1, B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Before the end of the year, the portion from SR&nbsp;94 to Home Avenue entered the bidding phase;<ref>{{cite news | title=State Asks Bids on Section of Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 15, 1971 | page=D4|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Guy F. Atkinson Company won the contract for roughly $9.96&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|9960000|1972|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) in early 1972.<ref>{{cite news | title=Long Beach Firm Awarded Contract | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 26, 1972 | page=B2|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Following a request from the El Cajon City Council,<ref>{{cite news | title=El Cajon Council to Ask Cycling on Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 2, 1972 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> March 19 was set aside as a Community Cycle Day for bicyclists to travel the newly finished freeway from El Cajon Boulevard to SR&nbsp;52, just before the freeway was to be dedicated the next day;<ref>{{cite news | title=Route 805 Bicycle Day Set March 19 | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 8, 1972 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> the entire Mission Valley Viaduct was open to traffic that month.<ref name=\"band\" />\n\nBy the beginning of 1974, I-805 was open north of Home Avenue, and from Otay Valley Road to Telegraph Canyon Road in Chula Vista;<ref name=\"band\" /> five segments remaining were under construction, and the last segment was funded.<ref>{{cite news | title=Public's Mood Shifts away from Freeways | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 8, 1974 | page=X16|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The Imperial Avenue section of I-805 remained in the budget, despite revisions in response to the [[1973 oil crisis]].<ref>{{cite news | title=County Road Share Set at $30 Million | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 12, 1974 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> In late January, I-805 between SR&nbsp;15 and SR&nbsp;94 was opened to traffic, though not all of the ramps at the SR&nbsp;94 interchange were operational.<ref>{{cite news | title=New Highway Link to Open | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 28, 1974 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The connectors to SR&nbsp;94 east were completed in March.<ref>{{cite news | title=805 Open to State 94 | work=The San Diego Union | date=March 7, 1974 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The entire portion between SR&nbsp;94 and Home Avenue cost $10.5&nbsp;million<ref name=\"band\" /> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|10500000|1974|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). Construction between SR&nbsp;94 and Imperial Avenue was well under way by December, at a cost of $8.5&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Continues Southward Advance | work=The San Diego Union | date=December 13, 1974 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|8500000|1974|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}).\n\nAs the scheduled completion of the freeway neared, Mayor Tom Hamilton of Chula Vista expressed concerns regarding the predicted development of the I-805 corridor, and the decisions that the City Council would need to make regarding such plans.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mayor Foresees Scramble for Sites as I-805 Develops | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 12, 1975 | author=Scaglione, Cecil | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The portion south of Otay Valley Road cost $15&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|15000000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}), and the portion between Telegraph Canyon Road and Sweetwater Road cost&nbsp;$12 million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|12000000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). The portion from there to Imperial Avenue was projected to cost $10.2&nbsp;million<ref name=\"band\" /> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|10200000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). The dedication of the freeway took place on July 23, 1975, even though the freeway was not entirely finished, due to the desire to hold the ceremony during the summer.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Dedicated but Opening Date Delayed | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 24, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> I-805 from Plaza Boulevard to Telegraph Canyon Road opened to traffic on July 28, leaving the freeway complete except for the portion between Plaza Boulevard and SR&nbsp;94. While portions of the freeway were nearly ready for traffic, there were reports of motorists driving on the closed freeway, which the [[California Highway Patrol]] warned was illegal.<ref>{{cite news | title=Unopened 805 Usage Prohibited | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 29, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> On September 3, Dekema announced that the entirety of the freeway would open the next day as he made a final inspection of the unopened portion; the total cost of the construction was $145&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|145000000|1975|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). However, Dekema announced that there was no more state funding available to construct further roads for the short-term.<ref>{{cite news | title=Officials Say Interstate 805 Is End of Road for Funds | work=The San Diego Union | date=September 4, 1975 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\n===Recognition, artwork, and architecture===\n[[Image:Miramar op 805.jpg|thumb|left|The La Jolla Village Drive overpass on I-805 northbound, with the Eastgate Mall bridge in the background]]\nThe Mission Valley Viaduct was recognized by the [[American Society of Civil Engineers]] (ASCE) as the \"Outstanding Civil Engineering Project for 1973 in the San Diego Area\"; it was designed to match the close by [[Mission San Diego de Alcal\u00e1]] with its columns that look similar to cathedral windows,<ref name=\"spectrum\" /> and arch-like shapes etched into the textured concrete. The viaduct was designed to span {{convert|3900|ft|m}}, and use squared-off support columns instead of traditional cylindrical supports. Octagonal columns were to be used on the ramps and the ends of the bridge.<ref>{{cite news | title=Bids Due Soon for Viaduct in Mission Valley | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 11, 1968 | author=Smith, Cliff | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Over 600&nbsp;tons of steel bars were to be used,<ref>{{cite news | title=Viaduct Takes Shape | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 7, 1969 | page=A28|oclc=13155544}}</ref> and the bridge was constructed as high as {{convert|98|ft|m}} above I-8.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Span Shows Geometric Beauty | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 24, 1970 | page=A3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The Adams Avenue Bridge over I-805 was also recognized for its {{convert|439|ft|m|adj=on}} span and two tapered supports on the ends of the bridge; in 1968, a [[Princeton University]] engineering professor asked for a copy of the design from Caltrans for educational purposes.<ref name=\"spectrum\">{{cite news | title=Bridges Span Design Spectrum | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 11, 1976 | page=F6|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The construction supervisor, in fact, compared the construction of this bridge to building a boat, and it was constructed from the middle outward rather than the conventional method of building from the ends inward. The span was designed to be {{convert|268|ft|m}} long,<ref>{{cite news | title=Boat-Like Curves Mark Overpass | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 11, 1968 | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> and {{convert|100|ft|m}} high.<ref>{{cite news | title=Interstate 805 Bridge Grows in Beauty | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 29, 1969 | page=A3|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nAwards for the Eastgate Mall (or Old Miramar Bridge) came from the [[Federal Highway Administration]], San Diego Highway Development Association, and Prestressed Concrete Institute Awards Program; at the time, it was one of the first arch bridges in the state, and did not use traditional concrete pillars.<ref name=\"spectrum\" /> The ''San Diego Union'' (predecessor to the ''Union-Tribune'') published a few freelance articles in 1984 about I-805, complimenting the four-level interchange with I-8 and the [[arch bridge]] at Eastgate Mall, while mentioning that subsequent inflation after their completion would have made such structures more difficult to build if they had been constructed later. Other artwork and architecture that was mentioned included the Wateridge development in Sorrento Valley, and the \"Stargazer\" building by Alexander Liberman that was lit with fluorescent colors at night.<ref>{{cite news | title=Outdoor Artworks Bring New Beauty to Freeway Travel | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 16, 1984 | author=Lewinson, David | page=E8|oclc=13155544}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Architecture at Its Best in S.D Freeways | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 26, 1984 | author=Jones, Bob | page=F1|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nHowever, not all forms of artwork along the highway were uncontroversial. In 1977, there were several complaints regarding new billboards that were installed at the northern terminus of the highway, since they blocked the view of the coast.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ruling Awaited on New Billboards On Interstate 805 | work=The San Diego Union | date=January 30, 1977 | author=Ball, Neil | page=B16|oclc=13155544}}</ref> In 1981, an illegal mural that was determined to be incomplete was discovered at the I-8 interchange; while Caltrans discouraged the painting of such murals, they were impressed with the portion that had already been completed.<ref>{{cite news | title=I-805 Graffiti Artist Sought | work=The San Diego Union | date=April 2, 1981 | author=Gross, Greg | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Art Cole, the artist, stepped forward to the department, and was allowed to finish the mural of a desert highland sunrise; following this, Caltrans made efforts to have other murals commissioned.<ref>{{cite news | title=Mural Is Given to San Diego | work=The San Diego Union | date=August 28, 1981 | page=B13|oclc=13155544}}</ref>\n\nThe San Ysidro Chamber of Commerce attempted to have I-805 named as the San Ysidro Freeway in 1976.<ref>{{cite news | title=Border Community Wants I-805 Named San Ysidro | work=The San Diego Union | date=July 16, 1976 | author=Scaglione, Cecil | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> However, I-805 was named after Jacob Dekema in August 1981, and ceremonies to mark the occasion occurred in February 1982.<ref name=\"dekema\">{{cite news | title=Father Of S.D. Freeways Now Has One of His Own | work=The San Diego Union | date=February 20, 1982 | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> The plaque honoring Dekema was installed in November at the Governor Drive interchange.<ref>{{cite news | title=Dekema Honored | work=The San Diego Union | date=November 23, 1982 | author=Romero, Bill | page=B3|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Because of his efforts in designing I-805, Ed Settle of Caltrans was given the Outstanding Civil Engineering Award from the ASCE; he designed several other regional freeways, including SR&nbsp;163 through [[Balboa Park (San Diego)|Balboa Park]] and I-5 through San Diego.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ed Settle: Designer Created Scenic Freeway in Balboa Park | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=April 3, 2005 | author=Williams, Jack | page=J5|oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\n[[File:Interstate 5 and Interstate 805 Sorrento Valley interchange.jpg|thumb|\"Dual freeway\" at northern I-805 terminus]]\nThe construction of a \"dual freeway\" at the northern end of I-805 was discussed as early as 1989, referring to the two [[carriageways]] needed for each direction of the freeway, resulting in four total. It would require drivers to use the new local lanes to access eastbound SR&nbsp;56 from I-5 or I-805. The project would allow for trucks to use the new lanes to assist in merging with traffic. However, it faced opposition from local residents, concerned about the loss of the view from their homes, as well as environmentalists concerned about nearby wetlands.<ref>{{cite news | title=Bottleneck at I-5/805 Is Dilemma | work=The San Diego Union | date=April 30, 1989 | author=Weisberg, Lori | page=B1|oclc=13155544}}</ref> Further objections espoused the view that the congestion would continue to increase, regardless of what was done, and that the new road would be at capacity in a few years.<ref>{{cite news | title=Residents Express Anguish at Plans to Expand I-5 Junction | work=Evening Tribune | date=June 2, 1989 | author=Kubik, Agnes | location=San Diego | page=B8|oclc=37687666}}</ref> The San Diego Association of Governments (SANDAG) funded the construction with $110 million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|110000000|2000|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}) in mid-2000.<ref>{{cite news | title=Highways Receive Bulk of Money in SANDAG Transportation Plan | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=July 22, 2000 | author=Arner, Mark | page=B3|oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\nConstruction of the \"dual freeway\" began in early 2002, at a cost of $182&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite news | title=I-5/805 Merge Widening Under Way | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=March 1, 2002 | last=LaRue | first=Steve | page=B2| oclc=25257675}}</ref> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-GDP|182000000|2002|r=3}}}} in {{inflation-year|US-GDP}}{{inflation-fn|US-GDP}}). The northbound lanes were scheduled to open in February 2006.<ref>{{cite news | title=Showers Push Back Opening of Bypass | work=The San Diego Union-Tribune | date=February 19, 2006 | page=B3| oclc=25257675}}</ref> The southbound lanes were completed in early 2007.<ref name=\"newlanes\" /> That year, a three-year project began to allow [[Driverless car|robot controlled vehicles]], including buses and trucks, to use a special lane.  The intention is to allow the vehicles to travel at shorter following distances and thereby allow more vehicles to use the lanes.  The vehicles will still have drivers since they need to enter and exit the special lanes. The system was designed by Swoop Technology, based in San Diego County.<ref name=\"RoboBus\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wired.com/cars/futuretransport/magazine/15-08/st_robot | title=Robot Buses Pull In to San Diego's Fastest Lane | work=Wired | date=July 24, 2007 | accessdate=August 19, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110112944/http://www.wired.com/cars/futuretransport/magazine/15-08/st_robot|archivedate=November 10, 2012 |oclc=24479723}}</ref>\n\nTwo years later, construction began on two auxiliary lanes on I-805 southbound from SR&nbsp;54 to Bonita Road, to improve traffic flow at the SR&nbsp;54 interchange.<ref>{{cite news | title=Short Takes | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=October 13, 2009 | author=Schmidt, Steve | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> In 2010, Caltrans proposed adding [[high-occupancy toll]] express lanes between SR&nbsp;15 and East Palomar Street in Chula Vista.<ref>{{cite news | title=Public Hearings Set on I-805 Expansion | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=September 21, 2010 | author=Fry, Wendy | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> The California Transportation Commission (CTC) awarded $100&nbsp;million for the work in June 2011, which would be split into two phases at the interchange with SR&nbsp;54.<ref>{{cite news | title=I-805 HOV-Lane Project Gets $100M from State | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=June 30, 2011 | author=Hawkins, Robert | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> Work is also underway to add two [[High-occupancy vehicle|HOV lanes]] between SR&nbsp;52 and Mira Mesa Boulevard; this project also received $59.5&nbsp;million from the CTC in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news | title=State Sending Region $82.6M for Road Work | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=September 19, 2011 | author=Hawkins, Robert | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> Meanwhile, SANDAG made arrangements to purchase the [[SR&nbsp;125 (CA)|SR&nbsp;125]] toll road and reduce the tolls, which was hoped to encourage commuters to take that road instead of I-805 and reduce congestion; this would then enable Caltrans to construct two managed lanes instead of the original four.<ref>{{cite news | title=SANDAG Agrees to Purchase South County Toll Road | work=San Diego Union-Tribune | date=December 17, 2011 | author=Hawkins, Robert | page=A1|oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, construction began on the northern HOV lanes; the project is expected to cost $86&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news | title=Express Lanes Project to Commence on I-805 | work=U-T San Diego | date=February 26, 2013 | author=Nichols, Chris | page=B2|oclc=25257675}}</ref> By May, construction on the Palomar Street direct access ramps had begun, and the Carroll Canyon Road ramps were almost finished.<ref>{{cite news | title=Ramps to Speed Access to I-15 | work=U-T San Diego | date=May 1, 2013 | author=Nichols, Chris | page=NC1|oclc=25257675}}</ref>  The northern project is expected to be complete in 2015,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist11/facts/805ManagedLanesNorth.pdf | format=PDF | title=Interstate 805 Express Lanes North Project Fact Sheet | publisher=California Department of Transportation | author=District 11 | date=June 2013 | accessdate=October 8, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928061742/http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist11/facts/805ManagedLanesNorth.pdf | archivedate=September 28, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> and the southern express lanes opened in March 2014 at a cost of $1.4&nbsp;billion, with an option to expand them into two lanes in each direction, and a proposed direct ramp to the express lanes.<ref>{{cite news | title=I-805 carpool lanes open in So. County | work=U-T San Diego | date=March 5, 2014 | author=Nichols, Chris | url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/mar/05/805-carpool-south-county-chula-vista-national-city/|oclc=25257675}}</ref> A 2012 Caltrans report proposed adding four managed lanes along the entire length of the highway.<ref name=\"TCR2\">{{cite web | author=Staff|url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/dist11/departments/planning/pdfs/tcs/2012_I_805_TCS.pdf | title=I-5 Transportation Concept Summary| publisher=Caltrans | date=June 2012 | accessdate=June 21, 2014 | format=PDF|pages=17}}</ref> Construction on HOV lanes from SR&nbsp;905 to SR&nbsp;15 is planned for 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title=Next phase for I-805 needs funding | work=U-T San Diego | date=May 8, 2014 | author=Nichols, Chris | page=NI7 | oclc=25257675}}</ref>\n\n==Exit list==\n{{CAinttop|exit|county=San Diego|post_ref=<br><ref name=trucklist /><ref name=traffic /><ref name=bridgelog>{{Caltrans bridgelog}}</ref>|exit_ref=<br /><ref>{{cite web |title=I-805 Northbound Freeway Interchanges |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivenorth.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=California Department of Transportation |work=California Numbered Exit Uniform System |access-date=February 5, 2009 |last=Howe |first=Don |date=August 16, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330012507/http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivenorth.pdf |archivedate= March 30, 2008 |location=Sacramento }}<br />{{cite web |title=I-805 Southbound Freeway Interchanges |url=http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivesouth.pdf |publisher=California Department of Transportation |work=California Numbered Exit Uniform System |access-date=February 5, 2009 |last=Howe |first=Don |date=August 16, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005032518/http://www.dot.ca.gov/trafficops/exit/docs/eightofivesouth.pdf |archivedate=October 5, 2009 |format=PDF |location=Sacramento }}</ref>\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=San Ysidro\n|lspan=5\n|postmile=0.15\n|exit=\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|I|5|dir1=south|location1=[[Mexico]] only}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; exit 1A on I-5\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|postmile=0.15\n|exit=1A\n|road=Camino de la Plaza\n|notes=Southbound exit and northbound entrance; last USA exit southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=0.65\n|exit=1B\n|road=San Ysidro Boulevard\n|notes=Signed as exit 1A northbound}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=1.81\n|exit=1C\n|road={{Jct|state=CA|SR|905}}\n|notes=Signed as exit 1B northbound; SR&nbsp;905 exit 2B; future [[Interstate 905|I-905]]\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=2.90\n|exit=2\n|road=Palm Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|location=Chula Vista\n|lspan=6\n|postmile=3.65\n|exit=3\n|road=Main Street / Auto Park Drive\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=4.42\n|exit=4\n|road=Olympic Parkway / E. Orange Avenue\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|type=hov\n|postmile=none\n|exit=\u2014\n|road=E. Palomar Street\n|notes=HOV access only; southbound left exit and northbound entrance\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=6.06\n|exit=6\n|road=L Street / Telegraph Canyon Road\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=7.16\n|exit=7\n|road=H Street\n|notes=Signed as exits 7A (east) and 7B (west) southbound\n}}\n{{CAint|exit\n|postmile=7.76\n|exit=7C\n|road=E Street / Bonita Road ([[County Route S17 (California)|CR&